-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''65.4%''' ''1,091''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|0.5% ''9''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[United States presidential election in Virginia, 1932|1932]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|35.4% ''551''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''63.5%''' ''988''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|1.0% ''16''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''[[United States presidential election in Virginia, 1928|1928]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''58.3%''' ''1,026''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|41.7% ''733''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;|\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[United States presidential election in Virginia, 1924|1924]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|34.1% ''549''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''63.5%''' ''1,022''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|2.4% ''38''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[United States presidential election in Virginia, 1920|1920]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|42.9% ''705''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''56.6%''' ''931''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|0.6% ''9''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[United States presidential election in Virginia, 1916|1916]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|37.3% ''311''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''61.3%''' ''511''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|1.3% ''11''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[United States presidential election in Virginia, 1912|1912]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|6.6% ''65''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''64.2%''' ''632''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|29.2% ''287''\n|}\n\nStaunton operates under a [[council-manager government|council-manager]] form of government. In 1908, Staunton was the first city in the United States to give an appointed employee authority over city affairs through statute. In 1912, [[Sumter, South Carolina|Sumter, S.C.]], was the first U.S. city to implement the council-manager form of city government.<ref>{{cite book | title = State & Local Politics: Institutions & Reform: The Essentials | url = https://archive.org/details/statelocalpoliti0000dono | url-access = registration |author1=Todd Donovan |author2=Daniel A. Smith |author3=Christopher Z. Mooney  |last-author-amp=yes | publisher = Cengage | year = 2010 | page = [https://archive.org/details/statelocalpoliti0000dono/page/265 265] | isbn = 0-495-56789-2}} [https://books.google.com/books?id=osYoxoTmCo4C& (available on Google books)]</ref>  The city of Staunton refers to itself on its website as the \"birthplace of President Woodrow Wilson, and the city manager form of government.\"<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.staunton.va.us/directory/departments-a-g/economic-development | title = Economic Development | publisher = City of Staunton | accessdate = August 17, 2011}}</ref>\n\nStaunton is part of [[Virginia's 6th congressional district]].\n\n===Sister cities===\n[[Vi\u015feu de Sus]], Romania.\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1860= 3875\n|1870= 5120\n|1880= 6664\n|1890= 6975\n|1900= 7289\n|1910= 10604\n|1920= 10623\n|1930= 11990\n|1940= 13337\n|1950= 19927\n|1960= 22232\n|1970= 24504\n|1980= 21857\n|1990= 24461\n|2000= 23853\n|2010= 23746\n|estyear=2019\n|estimate=24932\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2019\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2019.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n|align-fn=center\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/decennial-census.html|title=U.S. Decennial Census|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=January 6, 2014}}</ref><br />1790-1960<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mapserver.lib.virginia.edu|title=Historical Census Browser|publisher=University of Virginia Library|accessdate=January 6, 2014}}</ref> 1900-1990<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/population/cencounts/va190090.txt|title=Population of Counties by Decennial Census: 1900 to 1990|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=January 6, 2014}}</ref><br />1990-2000<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/population/www/cen2000/briefs/phc-t4/tables/tab02.pdf|title=Census 2000 PHC-T-4. Ranking Tables for Counties: 1990 and 2000|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=January 6, 2014}}</ref> 2010-2013<ref name=\"QF\" />\n}}\n\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name=\"GR8\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2011-05-14|title=U.S. Census website}}</ref> of 2000, there were 23,853 people, 9,676 households, and 5,766 families residing in the city. The [[population density]] was 1,210.3 people per square mile (467.3/km\u00b2). There were 10,427 housing units at an average density of 529.1 per square mile (204.3/km\u00b2). The racial makeup of the city was 83.29% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 13.95% [[African American (U.S. Census)|Black]] or [[Race (United States Census)|African American]], 0.22% [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 0.46% [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]], 0.01% [[Pacific Islander (U.S. Census)|Pacific Islander]], 0.52% from [[Race (United States Census)|other races]], and 1.55% from two or more races. [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race were 1.11% of the population.\n\nThere were 9,676 households out of which 24.9% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 44.4% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 11.7% had a female householder with no husband present, and 40.4% were non-families. 34.7% of all households were made up of individuals and 14.3% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.19 and the average family size was 2.81.\n\nIn the city, the population was spread out with 19.8% under the age of 18, 10.2% from 18 to 24, 27.8% from 25 to 44, 24.1% from 45 to 64, and 18.0% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 40 years. For every 100 females, there were 89.1 males. For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 87.0 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the city was $32,941, and the median income for a family was $44,422. Males had a median income of $30,153 versus $22,079 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the city was $19,161. About 7.7% of families and 11.7% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 15.9% of those under age 18 and 10.7% of those age 65 or over.\n\n==Economy==\n\n===Top employers===\nAccording to Staunton's 2015 Comprehensive Annual Financial Report,<ref>[http://www.staunton.va.us/directory/departments-a-g/finance/financial-reports-folder/comprehensive-annual-financial-report-cafr-june-30-2015 City of Staunton Comprehensive Annual Financial Report]</ref> the top employers in the city are:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\"\n|-\n! #\n! Employer\n! # of Employees\n|-\n| 1\n| [[Western State Hospital (Virginia)|Western State Hospital]]\n|500-599\n|-\n|2\n| Staunton City Schools\n|500-599\n|-\n|3\n| [[Mary Baldwin University]]\n|250-499\n|-\n|4\n| City of Staunton\n|250-499\n|-\n|5\n| [[Walmart]]\n|250-499\n|-\n|6\n| Fisher Auto Parts\n|250-499\n|-\n|7\n| Home Instead Senior Care\n|100-249\n|-\n|8\n| [[Cadence, Inc.]]\n|100-300\n|-\n|9\n| [[Virginia Department of Transportation|VDOT]]\n|100-249\n|-\n|10\n| [[Virginia School for the Deaf and the Blind]]\n|100-249\n|}\n\n==Culture==\n[[File:Coffee on the Corner building, Staunton, Virginia.jpg|thumb|right| The By & By Caf\u00e9 and Beer Garden, with [[Blackfriars Playhouse]] and the [[Stonewall Jackson Hotel]] behind]]\n[[File:StauntonVA Masonicbuilding.jpg|thumb|right|The Masonic Building]]\n\nStaunton is home to the [[American Shakespeare Center]], a theatrical company centered at the Blackfriars Playhouse, a replica of [[William Shakespeare|Shakespeare's]] [[Blackfriars Theatre]]. In 2012, it also became the home of the [http://www.heifetzinstitute.org/ Heifetz International Music Institute], named for renowned violinist [[Daniel Heifetz]], a summer music school and festival dedicated to the artistic growth and career development of some of the World's most talented and promising classical musicians. The [[Woodrow Wilson Presidential Library]] is open for visitors, as well as the [[Museum of American Frontier Culture]], which provides insight into life in early America.\n\nThe Staunton Music Festival \u2013 celebrating its 20th year in 2017 \u2013 features multiple concerts each day, with programs of music from the Renaissance to the present.  The festival takes place during the early part of August annually.  All performances take place at historic venues in downtown Staunton.<ref>http://stauntonmusicfestival.org/</ref>\n\nThe Queen City Mischief and Magic festival - celebrating its 4th year in 2019 - is a new but quickly-growing festival for Harry Potter fans, attracting over 10,000 people in its 3rd year. Visitors from all over the east coast come to take part in games, events, and shopping throughout downtown. Businesses contribute the activities for the festival and the majority of West Beverly St is shut down for the weekend event.\n\nStaunton is also the center of numerous galleries and art schools, the widely regarded Beverley Street Studio School and its associated Co-Art Gallery. In addition, Staunton is home to the Hypnagogia Film Collective, a collection of avant-garde experimental filmmakers.\n\nStaunton is home to the [[Statler Brothers]], [[country music]] legends who until 1994 performed free concerts at the annual [[Fourth of July]] celebration, accompanied by other country music artists.  Statler Brothers members [[Don Reid (singer)|Don Reid]], [[Harold Reid]], and [[Phil Balsley]] grew up and still reside in the city. [[Lew DeWitt]] was also a notable member of the Statlers who grew up in Staunton, VA.\n\n===Film===\nDowntown Staunton and Sherwood Avenue were used in the [[American Civil War]] film ''[[Gods and Generals (film)|Gods and Generals]]''. The local [[Shenandoah Valley Railroad (short-line)|Shenandoah Valley Railroad]] as well as a number of nearby houses were used in filming of ''[[Hearts in Atlantis (film)|Hearts in Atlantis]]''. In 1993,  a portion of the Showtime production of ''[[Assault at West Point: The Court-Martial of Johnson Whittaker]]'' was filmed here. In the summer of 2006, some scenes for the movie ''[[Evan Almighty]]'' were also filmed in Staunton. Some scenes for ''[[Familiar Strangers (film)|Familiar Strangers]]'' were also filmed in Staunton in 2007. In 2013, scenes from the documentary film [[Rita Dove: An American Poet]] were filmed in and around Staunton's [[Temple House of Israel]] synagogue.\n\n== Attractions ==\nStaunton is home to nearly 200 buildings designed by architect [[T. J. Collins|Thomas Jasper Collins]] (1844\u20131925), who worked in [[Victorian architecture|various styles]] during the [[Victorian era]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.readthehook.com/stories/2006/01/05/onArchitectureEyeCandyStau.html |title=Eye candy: Staunton cures visual blues |date=January 5, 2006 |accessdate=December 13, 2006 |publisher=[[The Hook (newspaper)|The Hook]]}}</ref> His firm, T. J. Collins & Sons, is still in business.\n\nThe city was once home to about ten hotels, but only one of them is still in operation - the [[Stonewall Jackson Hotel]]. This hotel was renovated in the early 2000s, and is now in operation as both a hotel and a conference center. The Ingleside Resort is no longer in operation.  During [[World War II]] it was used by the [[Immigration and Naturalization Service|INS]] as a [[Internment camp|detention center]] for [[enemy aliens]] held under [[Executive Order 9066]].<ref>{{cite book | title = Judgment without Trial: Japanese American Imprisonment during World War II | author = Tetsuden Kashima | page = [https://archive.org/details/judgmentwithoutt00kash/page/264 264] | year = 2004 | publisher = University of Washington Press | isbn = 0-295-98451-1 | url = https://archive.org/details/judgmentwithoutt00kash/page/264 }}</ref> Some of the hotels that are no longer in operation are [[Virginia Hotel|The Virginia Hotel]], the Eakleton Hotel, the [[Valley Hotel]], the [[American Hotel (Staunton, Virginia)|American Hotel]] and the Hotel Beverley. All of these buildings are still standing except for the Virginia Hotel, which was demolished in 1930 to make way for a planned addition to the Stonewall Jackson Hotel which was never built. The New Street Parking Garage now stands on the site.  Among the houses in Staunton on the National Register of Historic Places is ''[[The Oaks (Staunton, Virginia)|The Oaks]]'', at 437 East Beverley Street. An 1840s structure, it was modified and enlarged in 1888 by famed Civil War cartographer [[Jedediah Hotchkiss]]. Also on the National Register is ''[[Waverly Hill]]'', a Georgian-revival house designed in 1929 by renowned architect William Bottomley with a landscape designed by Arthur Shurcliff.\n\n===Parks and recreation===\n* Betsy Bell and Mary Gray Wilderness Parks \u2014 a {{convert|70|acre|m2|adj=on}} mountaintop park with a {{convert|1959|ft|m}} observation platform\n* [[Gypsy Hill Park]] \u2014 a {{convert|214|acre|m2|adj=on}} multi-use facility with a golf course, football and baseball stadiums, gymnasium, lake, two playgrounds, three youth baseball fields, public swimming pool, volleyball court, horseshoe pits, tennis courts, the Gypsy Express mini-train, the Duck Pond, a skatepark, a bandstand, and several pavilions.  Until the Staunton city parks were integrated, Gypsy Hill Park was only open to whites<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.whsv.com/news/headlines/24819959.html | title = Staunton's Other Park | publisher = WHSV-TV | author = Keith Jones | date = July 12, 2008 | accessdate = August 17, 2011}}</ref> except for one day a year, which was set aside for other races to use the park.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://augustafreepress.com/the-true-story-of-stauntons-other-park/ | title = The true story of \u2018Staunton\u2019s Other Park\u2019 | author = Chris Graham | date = July 10, 2008 | publisher = Augusta Free Press | accessdate = August 17, 2011}}</ref>\n* Montgomery Hall Park \u2014 a {{convert|148|acre|m2|adj=on}} multi-use facility with softball and soccer fields, tennis courts, disc golf course,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pdga.com/course/courses_by_city.php?id=2086 |title=PDGA Disc Golf Course Details &#124; Professional Disc Golf Association |publisher=Pdga.com |date= |accessdate=June 14, 2009}}</ref> playgrounds, picnic shelters, hiking and mountain biking trails, and a swimming pool (which was renovated in 2016 after being closed since 2010.)<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.newsleader.com/story/news/local/2016/07/17/new-pool-montgomery-hall-draws-swimmers/87220848/ | title = New pool at Montgomery Hall draws swimmers | publisher = The Staunton News Leader | date = July 17, 2016 | author = William Ramsey | accessdate = May 13, 2019}}</ref> The offices of the Department of Parks and Recreation are at the Irene Givens Administration building, which also includes a kitchen, activity room, and conference room which are available for public use.  Montgomery Hall Park was opened in 1950 after much agitation by non-white residents of Staunton.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://orig.newsleader.com/communities/overview/africans.html | title = Area Overview: History -- African-Americans | publisher = The Staunton News Leader | accessdate = August 17, 2011}}</ref>  Before segregation ended in the mid-1960s, Montgomery Hall park was the only park in the city open to African-Americans<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.staunton.va.us/directory/departments-h-z/recreation-parks/parks/montgomery-hall-park | title = Montgomery Hall Park entry on Staunton City website | accessdate = July 31, 2011}}</ref>\n* Booker T. Washington Community Center \u2014 formerly the segregated Booker T. Washington High School, although according to the court which decided Bell v. Staunton Board of Education, the term \"high school\" was a misnomer, as the school also contained \"first, second, and seventh grade classes and two special mentally retarded classes as well as the eighth through the twelfth grades.\"<ref name=bell />\n* Nelson Street Teen Center \u2014 closed ({{As of|2011|lc=y}}) due to budget cuts.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.staunton.va.us/directory/departments-h-z/recreation-parks/facilities-rentals/nelson-street-teen-center | publisher = City of Staunton | title = Nelson Street Teen Center | accessdate = August 14, 2011}}</ref>\n*Landes Park - a small, one-acre park names after Walter James Landes, Jr. in 1993. Near downtown Staunton.<ref name=\"Small Parks {{!}} City of Staunton\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ci.staunton.va.us/departments/parks-recreation-/parks/smaller-parks|title=Small Parks {{!}} City of Staunton|website=www.ci.staunton.va.us|access-date=2019-12-02}}</ref>\n*Reservoir Hill Park - a small four acres park located at the old city reservoir.<ref name=\"Small Parks {{!}} City of Staunton\"/>\n*Men's Green Thumb Park - approximately two acres and was created through a joint sponsorship by the Men's Green Thumb Garden Club and United Virginia Bank National Valley, 1960\u20131970.<ref name=\"Small Parks {{!}} City of Staunton\"/>\n*Knowles Park - Knowles Park is a small parcel of land directly across from the main entrance of Gypsy Hill Park.<ref name=\"Small Parks {{!}} City of Staunton\"/>\n*Woodrow Park (Sears Hill) - approximately five acres and is located in the Sears Hill District of Staunton. The park was named in honor of President Woodrow Wilson and features a scenic overlook of historic downtown Staunton.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ci.staunton.va.us/departments/parks-recreation-/parks/woodrow-park-sears-hill-copy|title=Woodrow Park|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Sports==\nIn 1894, Staunton fielded a baseball team in the original [[Virginia League (1894-1896)|Virginia League]]: The Hayseeds.<ref name=minor>{{cite web | url = https://www.baseball-reference.com/minors/team.cgi?city=Staunton&state=VA&country=US | title = Staunton, Virginia Minor League City Encyclopedia | accessdate = August 3, 2011}}</ref>  In 1914, the city fielded a team in the [[Virginia Mountain League]]: The Staunton Lunatics.<ref name=minor />  The Lunatics moved to Harrisonburg in July 1914, just before the league disbanded.<ref name=bbref>{{cite web | url = https://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/Virginia_Mountain_League | title = Virginia Mountain League | publisher = baseball-reference.com | accessdate = August 3, 2011}}</ref>  From 1939 to 1942, the city fielded a team in the second [[Virginia League (1939-1942)|Virginia League]]: the Staunton Presidents.<ref name=minor />  Staunton currently has no minor league baseball, but the [[Staunton Braves]] represent the city in the [[Valley Baseball League]], a [[collegiate summer baseball]] league that plays in the Shenandoah Valley.\n\n==Infrastructure==\n\n===Transportation===\n====Roads and highways====\n[[File:2016-05-19 17 21 59 View north along Commerce Road (U.S. Route 11) just north of Woodrow Wilson Parkway (Virginia State Route 262) in Staunton, Virginia.jpg|thumb|right|US 11 in Staunton]]\nThe main highways through Staunton include [[U.S. Route 11 in Virginia|U.S. Route 11]], [[U.S. Route 11 Business (Staunton, Virginia)|U.S. Route 11 Business]], [[U.S. Route 250 in Virginia|U.S. Route 250]], [[Virginia State Route 252]], [[Virginia State Route 254]], [[Virginia State Route 261]] and [[Virginia State Route 262]]. U.S. Route 11 and U.S. Route 250 are the most prominent roads passing directly through Staunton, with US 11 following a northeast to southwest alignment (but signed north\u2013south), and US 250 following a northwest to southeast alignment (but signed east\u2013west). US 11 Business follows a slower route through downtown compared to the main US 11 routing which passes just outside downtown. State Routes 252 and 254 are minor roads leading to nearby rural areas of adjacent Augusta County. State Route 261 provides a better route for trucks following US 11 and US 250 through the city. State Route 262 forms a limited access beltway around the outskirts of Staunton. [[Interstate 64 in Virginia|Interstate 64]] and [[Interstate 81 in Virginia|Interstate 81]] both pass just outside the city limits and provide the main high-speed, high-volume roads to the Staunton region.\n\n====Public transportation====\n{{see also |Staunton (Amtrak station)}}\n[[File:Staunton Amtrak station.jpg|thumb|right|[[Staunton (Amtrak station)|Staunton Amtrak station]]]]\nStaunton is served by [[Amtrak]]'s ''[[Cardinal (train)|Cardinal]]''. The train station, which is located downtown, is the closest station to the nearby cities of [[Harrisonburg, Virginia|Harrisonburg]] and [[Lexington, Virginia|Lexington]]. The [[Buckingham Branch]] also has a small railyard.\n\nStaunton had a municipal bus system during the 20th century, known as the Staunton Transit Service, but it was dissolved in 1989.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://commonwealthcoach.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=66&Itemid=78 | title = 1973 GMC TDH3302 Staunton Transit at Commonwealth Coach and Trolley | accessdate = July 31, 2011}}</ref>  In 1944, [[World War II]] veteran S. Melvin Johnson wrote to [[Truman Gibson]], assistant to [[William H. Hastie]], advisor to Secretary of War [[Henry L. Stimson]], regarding segregated seating on the Staunton Transit Service and stating that returning African-American soldiers would not stand for such conditions.<ref>Letter from S. Melvin Johnson to Truman Gibson, collected in Subject Files of Judge William H. Hastie, Civilian Aide to the Secretary of War, \"N\" through \"Z\". National Archives, College Park, Maryland.</ref> This letter was an indication of the role that African-American veterans would later play in the [[American civil rights movement]].  In 1946, after the [[United States Supreme Court]] decision ''[[Irene Morgan v. Commonwealth of Virginia]]'', which found that Virginia's segregated seating law was unconstitutional with respect to interstate bus routes, Ethel New, a black woman from [[Lynch, Kentucky]], was arrested for violating the law because she had purchased an intrastate ticket.<ref name=back>{{cite news|title=Must Occupy Back Seat, VA Supreme Court says|work=The Afro American|date=September 6, 1947|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=Yh0mAAAAIBAJ&sjid=vv0FAAAAIBAJ&pg=4251%2C1151045}}</ref>  New suffered a miscarriage subsequent to her arrest and sued [[Greyhound Lines]] and the arresting officer in Staunton.<ref name=back/> In September 1947, meeting in Staunton, the [[Virginia Supreme Court of Appeals]] upheld the all-white jury's verdict exonerating both the bus line and the officer.<ref name=back/>\n\nBlue Ridge Intercity Transit Express (BRITE) provides fixed-route transit bus service in Staunton on three routes: the Downtown Trolley, West Route, and North Route.<ref>{{cite web|title=BRITE Bus Transit Services|url=http://britebus.org/}}</ref> The Coordinated Area Transportation Services (CATS) operates a demand-response service throughout the Staunton area, as well as a fixed shuttle service between the downtown areas of Staunton and Waynesboro.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.staunton.va.us/community/transportation/cats|title=Staunton VA|publisher=|accessdate=July 3, 2016}}</ref> Virginia Breeze provides intercity bus service between [[Blacksburg, Virginia|Blacksburg]] and [[Washington, D.C.|Washington]], with a stop in Staunton.<ref>{{Cite web| title = The Virginia Breeze: Bus from Blacksburg to Washington, DC| work = The Virginia Breeze: Bus from Blacksburg to Washington, DC {{!}} DRPT| accessdate = 2020-01-20| url = https://virginiabreeze.org/}}</ref>\n\nThe city is adjacent to the northernmost junction of [[I-81]] and [[I-64]]. [[Virginia State Route 262]] forms a partial beltway around the city, and both [[U.S. Route 250 in Virginia|US 250]] and [[U.S. Route 11 in Virginia|US 11]] pass through the city.\n\nThe nearest commercial airport is [[Shenandoah Valley Regional Airport]] in [[Weyers Cave, Virginia]].\n\n===Healthcare===\n* [[Commonwealth Center for Children and Adolescents]] (formerly the DeJarnette Center after [[eugenicist]] [[Joseph DeJarnette]]) psychiatric facility\n* [[Western State Hospital (Virginia)]] psychiatric facility\n\n==Education==\n[[File:Robert E. Lee High School, Staunton, VA.jpg|thumb|[[Staunton High School]]]]\n[[Staunton City Schools]] is the school district of the city.\n\nBlack Virginians were largely barred from education until [[Reconstruction Era of the United States|Reconstruction]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.vahistorical.org/civilrights/education.htm | title = Beginnings of Black Education | publisher = Virginia State Historical Society | year = 2004 | accessdate = August 5, 2011}}</ref>  The first school in Staunton which allowed African-Americans to attend was established by the [[Freedmen's Bureau]] under the supervision of the commanding general of the occupying [[Union army]] in late 1865.  Arrangements were made to bring in women from the North as teachers, and the jury rooms of the [[Augusta County Courthouse]], located at 1 E. Johnson Street, were to be used as classrooms.  The court protested this plan, however, and it is possible that another location was found.<ref>{{cite news | date = October 31, 1865 | newspaper = Staunton Spectator | page = 3 | title = Freedmen's School | url = http://valley.lib.virginia.edu/news/ss1865/va.au.ss.1865.10.31.xml#03 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1964 the Staunton chapter of the [[NAACP]] threatened the city with a lawsuit if they did not immediately desegregate the public schools.<ref name=pupil>{{cite news|work=The Free Lance-Star|date=May 12, 1964|title=Staunton Keeps Pupil System, Faces Suit|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=-dhNAAAAIBAJ&sjid=w4oDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6407%2C3742337}}</ref>  The City School Board, headed by Thomas W. Dixon, declined to take further action, contending that the schools were already desegregated as ten black children had been allowed to attend previously all-white schools.<ref name=pupil/> Attorneys for the city of Staunton submitted a plan for the [[desegregation]] of its public schools in 1965 by eliminating all negro schools in time for the 1967\u20131968 school year, which was approved by the [[Department of Health, Education and Welfare]].  However, the implementation of this plan was delayed to such an extent that a group of African-American parents brought suit in the [[United States District Court for the Western District of Virginia]] against the city. This case, ''Bell v. School Board of Staunton'', was decided on January 5, 1966, with the court stating that the delay was a violation of the rights of the students under the [[Fourteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Fourteenth Amendment]] and ordering that the schools and their faculty be desegregated in time for the 1966\u20131967 school year.<ref name=bell>{{cite web | url = http://va.findacase.com/research/wfrmDocViewer.aspx/xq/fac.19660105_0000001.WVA.htm/qx | title = Bell v. School Board of Staunton at findacase | accessdate = July 30, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe Staunton city school district was one of 21 in Virginia which take elementary school students out of class for Bible lessons on a voluntary basis, a practice known as [[Weekday Religious Education]].<ref name=donations/> Although the [[U.S. Supreme Court]] ended taxpayer-funded religious education in 1948 in ''[[McCollum v. Board of Education]]'', four years later they opened the door to privately funded voluntary classes held during school hours but away from school premises in ''[[Zorach v. Clauson]]''. In 2005, a group of parents in Staunton asked the school board to halt the practice.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A29266-2005Jan22.html | publisher = The Washington Post | date = January 23, 2005 | title = Bible Breaks at Public Schools Face Challenges in Rural Virginia | author = Carol Morello | accessdate = July 31, 2011}}</ref>  The challenge was successful, and the Bible classes are no longer being taught as of April 2017.<ref name=donations>{{cite news|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:AWNB:NVIR&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=146F7069EFDA7918&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D663DC0A81A15EA|title=Donations needed to keep Religious Ed program operating|work=The News-Virginian|author=Bob Stuart|date=June 16, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Public===\nDistrict schools:\n* T.C. McSwain Elementary School\n* A.R. Ware Elementary School\n* Bessie Weller Elementary School\n* Shelburne Middle School\n* [[Staunton High School]]\n* Dixon Educational Center (includes Genesis Alternative Education Program)\nState-operated:\n* [[Virginia School for the Deaf and Blind]]\n\n===Private===\n* [[Stuart Hall School]]\u2014preparatory school (boarding for coed, day school for coed)\n* Grace Christian School\u2014Coed Christian School for Pre-K to 12th Grade\n* C. F. Richards Jr. Academy\u2014coed Seventh-Day Adventist school\n* [[Mary Baldwin University]]\u2014Private liberal arts college, formerly a women's college\n* Raw Learning \u2014 democratic / free school\n\n==Media==\n* ''[[The News Leader]]'', local newspaper.  Owned by the [[Gannett Company]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.newsleader.com | title = News Leader web site | accessdate = August 5, 2011}}</ref>\n* [[WHSV-TV|WHSV]]. [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] affiliate in [[Harrisonburg, Virginia|Harrisonburg]].\n* [[WKDW-AM]]. [[Clear Channel Communications]].\n* [[WQSV-LP]]. [[Community radio]] station.\n\n==Notable people==\n[[File:Thomas Woodrow Wilson.jpg|thumb|President [[Woodrow Wilson]]]]\n{{Colbegin|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Diana Adams]], dancer\n* [[Charles W. Anderson]], awarded the [[Medal of Honor]]\n* [[John Brown Baldwin]], legislator\n* [[Mary Julia Baldwin]], educator\n* [[Phil Balsley]], Tenor singer for [[The Statler Brothers]]\n* [[Randolph C. Berkeley]], [[Major general (United States)|major general]] in the [[United States Marine Corps]], awarded the [[Medal of Honor]]\n* [[Larry Boerner]], baseball pitcher\n* [[Allen Caperton Braxton]], segregationist and Staunton representative to the [[revanchist]] Virginia [[Virginia Constitutional Convention of 1902|state constitutional convention of 1902]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.encyclopediavirginia.org/Braxton_A_Caperton_1862-1914 | title = A. Caperton Braxton (1862\u20131914) | publisher = Encyclopedia of Virginia | accessdate = August 19, 2011}}</ref>\n* [[John Breckinridge (U.S. Attorney General)|John Breckinridge]], senator and attorney general\n* [[Joseph Calhoun]], congressman\n* [http://lsupress.org/books/detail/from-slave-to-statesman/ Willis M. Carter], teacher, civil rights advocate, newspaper editor\n* [[William Christian (Virginia)|William Christian]], soldier and politician\n* [[Gertrude Harris Boatwright Claytor]], poet\n* [[George M. Cochran]], Virginia Supreme Court Justice\n* [[John E. Colhoun]], senator and lawyer\n* [[Francis Collins (geneticist)|Francis Collins]], Director of the [[NIH]]\n* [[Joseph DeJarnette]], psychiatrist and eugenicist\n* [[Lew DeWitt]], Tenor singer for [[The Statler Brothers]]\n* [[Joseph W. Fifer]], governor of Illinois\n* [[Dave Fultz]], baseball center fielder\n* [[Armistead C. Gordon]], author, professor of English at the [[University of Virginia]]<ref>{{cite news|publisher=New York Times|title=A. C. Gordon Jr. Dies; Virginia Professor|date=May 14, 1953|page=29}}</ref>\n* [[William Haines]], film actor and interior designer\n* [[Wade H. Haislip]], four-star general\n* [[Emmett Hanger]], politician\n* [[Kenton Harper]], printer, soldier and politician\n* [[George Moffett Harrison]], judge\n* [[Alexander Hart]], major in the [[Confederate States Army|Confederate Army]]\n* [[John N. Hendren]], judge and treasurer of the [[Confederate States of America]]\n* [[Henry W. Holt]], chief justice of the Virginia Supreme Court of Appeals<ref>{{cite news|publisher=New York Times|title=Henry W. Holt Dies; A Virginia Jurist, 83|date=October 5, 1947|page=68}}</ref>\n* [[Thomas D. Howie]], teacher and military officer\n* [[Alexander Humphreys]], physician\n* [[Parry Wayne Humphreys]], congressman\n* [[Carroll Knicely]], editor and publisher\n* [[Shannon Lucas]], drummer\n* [[Sampson Mathews]], soldier and politician\n* [[Jerry Lee May]], baseball catcher for the Pittsburgh Pirates and Kansas City Royals\n* [[Samuel Augustus Merritt]], delegate and judge\n* [[James Coffield Mitchell]], congressman\n* [[Samuel Morgan]], businessman, builder and manufacturer\n* [[Ethel Moses]], actress and dancer\n* [[Eustace Mullins]], [[white supremacist]], [[anti-semite]], [[conspiracy theorist]], author, and publisher of Revelation Books.<ref>{{cite journal | title = Right Rebellious - Guru Wages a War of Words on Conservatism's Fringe  | journal = Richmond Times-Dispatch | date = May 10, 1995 | author = Bill McKelway}}</ref>\n* [[Wilton Persons]], chief assistant to [[Dwight D. Eisenhower]] and superintendent of Staunton Military Academy<ref>{{cite news|publisher=New York Times|title=Wilton B. Persons is Dead at 81; Chief Assistant to Eisenhower|page=42|date=September 6, 1977}}</ref>\n* [[Don Reid (singer)|Don Reid]], lead singer and songwriter for [[The Statler Brothers]]\n* [[Harold Reid]], bass singer for [[The Statler Brothers]]\n* [[Larry Sheets]], baseball outfielder and designated hitter\n* [[John B. Stephenson]], sociologist\n* [[Alexander Hugh Holmes Stuart]], congressman, [[United States Secretary of the Interior|secretary of the interior]], and chairman of the [[Committee of Nine]]\n* [[Jacob Swoope]], politician\n* [[Malfourd W. Trumbo]], politician and judge\n* [[A. J. Turner]], teacher of music, first director of Stonewall Brigade Band\n* [[Thomas Wilson (Virginia politician)|Thomas Wilson]], congressman\n* [[Woodrow Wilson]], 28th president of the United States\n* [[Larry Woodall]], baseball catcher\n* [[Jacob Yost (Virginia congressman)|Jacob Yost]], congressman\n{{Colend}}\n* [[Dr. Ralph Cohen]], American Shakespeare Center founder, author, and professor\n\n==See also==\n* [[National Register of Historic Places listings in Staunton, Virginia]]\n* [[U.S. Route 11 Business (Staunton, Virginia)|U.S. Route 11 Business]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n{{wikivoyage|Staunton (Virginia)|Staunton, Virginia}}\n{{NSRW Poster|Staunton, Va.}}\n* [http://www.staunton.va.us/ City of Staunton, Virginia]\n* [http://www.librarytechnology.org/lwc-displaylibrary.pl?RC=8682 Staunton Public Library]\n* [http://www.augustacountyhs.org/ Augusta County Historical Society & Museum]\n* [http://www.stauntonperformingarts.org/ Staunton Performing Arts Center]\n* [http://www.heifetzinstitute.org/ Heifetz International Music Institute]\n* [http://stauntonmusicfestival.org/ Staunton Music Festival ]\n* [http://encyclopediavirginia.org/Staunton_During_the_Civil_War Staunton During the Civil War in ''Encyclopedia Virginia'']\n* {{curlie |/Regional/North_America/United_States/Virginia/Localities/S/Staunton/ |Staunton}}\n\n{{Virginia}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Staunton, Virginia| ]]\n[[Category:County seats in Virginia]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1747]]\n[[Category:1747 establishments in Virginia]]\n[[Category:Cities in Virginia]]\n[[Category:Western Virginia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2014}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n |name = Staunton, Virginia\n\n|settlement_type = [[Independent city (United States)|Independent city]]\n|nickname = Queen City of the Shenandoah Valley\n|motto = \n|image_skyline = City-Scape-Sunrise slideshow.jpg\n|image_caption = Overlook of downtown Staunton during sunrise\n|image_flag = File:Staunton flag1.png\n|image_seal = File:Staunton coat.jpg\n|pushpin_map  = Shenandoah Valley#USA Virginia#USA\n|pushpin_label = Staunton\n| subdivision_type = Country\n|subdivision_name = United States\n|subdivision_type1 = [[U.S. state|State]]\n|subdivision_name1 = [[Virginia]]\n|subdivision_type2 = [[County]]\n|subdivision_name2 = None ([[Independent city (United States)|Independent city]])\n|government_footnotes = \n|government_type = \n|leader_title = \n|leader_name = \n|leader_title1 = \n|leader_name1 = \n|established_title = [[Incorporation (municipal government)|Incorporated]]\n|established_date = 1801\n|unit_pref = Imperial\n|area_footnotes = <ref name=\"CenPopGazetteer2016\">{{cite web|title=2018 U.S. Gazetteer Files|url=https://www2.census.gov/geo/docs/maps-data/data/gazetteer/2018_Gazetteer/2018_gaz_place_51.txt|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=Feb 16, 2020}}</ref>\n|area_magnitude = \n|area_total_sq_mi = 19.98\n|area_land_sq_mi = 19.92\n|area_water_sq_mi = 0.06\n|population_as_of         = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n|population_footnotes = \n|population_total = 23746\n|population_density_sq_mi = auto\n|timezone  = [[North American Eastern Time Zone|Eastern (EST)]]\n|utc_offset = \u22125\n|timezone_DST = EDT\n|utc_offset_DST = \u22124\n|elevation_footnotes = \n|elevation_m = 432\n|elevation_ft = 1417\n|coordinates     = {{coord|38|9|29|N|79|4|35|W|region:US-VA_type:city|display=inline,title}}\n|postal_code_type = [[ZIP code]]s\n|postal_code = 24401-24402\n|area_code = [[Area code 540|540]]\n|blank_name = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info = 51-75216<ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2008-01-31|title=U.S. Census website}}</ref>\n|blank1_name = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank1_info = 1500154<ref name=\"GR3\">{{cite web|url=http://geonames.usgs.gov|accessdate=2008-01-31|title=US Board on Geographic Names|publisher=[[United States Geological Survey]]|date=2007-10-25}}</ref>\n|website = http://www.staunton.va.us/\n|footnotes = \n|pop_est_as_of = 2019\n|pop_est_footnotes = <ref name=\"USCensusEst2019\"/>\n|population_est = 24932\n}}\n\n'''Staunton''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|s|t|\u00e6|n|t|\u0259n}} {{respell|STAN|t\u0259n}}) is an [[independent city (United States)|independent city]] in the [[U.S. Commonwealth]] of [[Virginia]]. As of the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]], the population was 23,746.<ref name=\"QF\">{{cite web|title=State & County QuickFacts|url=http://quickfacts.census.gov/qfd/states/51/51790.html|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=January 6, 2014}}</ref> In Virginia, independent cities are separate jurisdictions from the counties that surround them, so the government offices of [[Augusta County, Virginia|Augusta County]] are in [[Verona, Virginia|Verona]], which is contiguous to Staunton.<ref name=\"GR6\">{{cite web|url=http://www.naco.org/Counties/Pages/FindACounty.aspx|accessdate=2011-06-07|title=Find a County|publisher=National Association of Counties}}</ref>\n\nStaunton is a principal city of the Staunton-[[Waynesboro, Virginia|Waynesboro]] [[Staunton-Waynesboro, VA Metropolitan Statistical Area|Metropolitan Statistical Area]], which had a 2010 population of 118,502.\n\nStaunton is known for being the birthplace of [[Woodrow Wilson]], the 28th [[U.S. president]], and as the home of [[Mary Baldwin University]], historically a women's college. The city is also home to [[Stuart Hall School|Stuart Hall]], a private co-ed [[University preparatory school|preparatory school]], as well as the [[Virginia School for the Deaf and Blind]]. It was the first city in the United States with a fully defined city manager system.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Bird's-eye View of Staunton, VA.jpg|thumb|left|Bird's-eye view c. 1910]]\nThe area was first settled in 1732 by John Lewis and family. In 1736, [[William Beverley]], a wealthy planter and [[merchant]] from [[Essex County, Virginia|Essex County]], was granted by the [[The Crown|Crown]] over {{convert|118,000|acres|abbr=off}} in what would become Augusta County. [[surveying|Surveyor]] [[Thomas Lewis (Virginia)|Thomas Lewis]] in 1746 laid out the first town [[plat]] for Beverley of what was originally called Beverley's Mill Place.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.roanetnhistory.org/bookread.php?loc=WaddellsAnnals&pgid=64 |title=Chapter 3: From the First Court to the First Indian War - Page 52, Waddell's Annals of Augusta County, Virginia, from 1726 to 1871 |publisher=Roanetnhistory.org |date= |accessdate=June 14, 2009}}</ref> Founded in 1747, it was renamed in honor of Lady Rebecca Staunton, wife to Royal Lieutenant-Governor [[Sir William Gooch, 1st Baronet|Sir William Gooch]].<ref name=room>{{cite book |last= Room |first= Adrian |title= Dictionary of World Place Names Derived from British Names |year= 1989 |publisher= Taylor & Francis |isbn= 978-0-415-02811-0|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=7JEOAAAAQAAJ&lpg=PP1&pg=PP1 |pages= 168}}</ref> Because the town was located at the geographical center of the colony (which then included [[West Virginia]]), Staunton served between 1738 and 1771 as regional capital for what was known as the Northwest Territory, with the westernmost [[courthouse]] in [[British North America]] prior to the [[American Revolution|Revolution]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.co.augusta.va.us/Index.aspx?page=422 |title=Augusta County, VA : History |publisher=Co.augusta.va.us |accessdate=June 14, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140627171457/http://www.co.augusta.va.us/Index.aspx?page=422 |archivedate=June 27, 2014 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> By 1760, Staunton was one of the major \"remote trading centers in the backcountry\" which coordinated the transportation of the vast amounts of grain and tobacco then being produced in response to the change of [[Great Britain|Britain]] from a net exporter of produce to an importer.  Staunton thus played a crucial role in the mid 18th century expansion of the economies of the [[American Colonies]] which, in turn, contributed to the success of the [[American Revolution]].<ref>{{cite book | author = Gordon S. Wood | title = The American Revolution: a history | publisher = Modern Library | year = 2002 | page = [https://archive.org/details/americanrevoluti00gord/page/13 13] | isbn = 0-679-64057-6 | url-access = registration | url = https://archive.org/details/americanrevoluti00gord/page/13 }}</ref> It served as capital of Virginia in June 1781, when state [[Virginia General Assembly|legislators]] fled [[Richmond, Virginia|Richmond]] and then [[Charlottesville, Virginia|Charlottesville]] to avoid capture by the [[British people|British]].\n\n[[File:Stauntonslavetrade.jpg|thumb|Lewis Miller, Sketchbook of Landscapes in the State of Virginia, 1853\u20131867. Courtesy, Abby Aldrich Rockefeller Folk Art Museum, Colonial Williamsburg Foundation, Williamsburg, Virginia; slide 84-896c.Titled, \"Slave trader, Sold to Tennessee.\" The caption states: \" The company going to Tennessee from Staunton, Augusta county, the law of Virginia suffered them to go on. I was astonished at this boldness, the carrier stopped a moment, then ordered the march, I saw the play it is commonly in this state, when the negro\u2019s in droves Sold.\" | left]]\n\nLike most of colonial Virginia, [[Slaves#Americas|slavery]] was present in Staunton. For instance, in 1815, a slave named Henry ran away from John G. Wright's Staunton plantation. Wright placed an ad in the [[Daily National Intelligencer]] in [[Washington, D.C.]] seeking Henry's return. It notes that Henry was an excellent cook and was widely travelled, having been as far as the [[West Indies]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://historyengine.richmond.edu/episodes/view/3494 | title = Wanted: Experienced Cook, World Traveler, Runaway Slave | publisher = The History Engine at the University of Richmond | accessdate = August 2, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===The Civil War and immediately prior===\n[[File:1861.08.06.daily.constitutionalist.page.one.letter.from.mayor.of.staunton.virginia.jpg|thumb|200px|Letter from N.K. Trout, mayor of Staunton, describing a contribution of $80 to the [[1st Georgia Infantry|1st Georgia Regiment]], then encamped at [[Monterey, Virginia]].  Published in the ''Daily Constitutionalist'' of [[Augusta, Georgia]] on August 6, 1861]]\nIn August 1855, President [[Franklin Pierce]] visited Staunton.  He gave a speech at the [[Virginia Hotel]], in which he stated that his \"feelings revolted from the idea of a dissolution of the union.\"  He said that \"[i]t would be the Iliad of innumerable woes, from the contemplation of which he shrank.\"<ref>{{cite news|publisher=New York Daily Times (reprinted from the Staunton Vindicator)|date=August 22, 1855|page=1|title=The President in Staunton, Va.}}</ref>\n\nLocated along the [[Valley Pike]], Staunton developed as a [[trade]], transportation and industrial center, particularly after the [[Virginia Central Railroad]] arrived in 1854. [[Factory|Factories]] made [[carriage]]s, [[wagon]]s, [[boot]]s and [[shoemaking|shoes]], [[clothing]] and [[blanket]]s.<ref name=ev /> In 1860, the [[Staunton Military Academy]] was founded. By 1860, Staunton had at least one pro-Union, pro-slavery<ref>{{cite web|title=The Sensible Negro|url=http://valley.lib.virginia.edu/news/ss1860/va.au.ss.1860.09.25.xml#02|website=Valley of the Shadow: Civil War-Era Newspapers|publisher=Valley of the Shadow|accessdate=11 March 2016}}</ref> (the ''[[The Valley of the Shadow|Staunton Spectator]]'') and at least one pro-secession, pro-slavery newspaper (the ''[[The Valley of the Shadow|Staunton Vindicator]]'').<ref>{{cite web | url = http://courses.cit.cornell.edu/hist100.06/kim/essay.html | title = A Disunited South: Augusta and its Pro-Unionists | author = Fritz Umbach | accessdate = August 2, 2011}}</ref>  The ''Spectator'' ran editorials before the war urging its citizens to vote for union,<ref>{{cite web | url = http://valley.lib.virginia.edu/news/ss1860/va.au.ss.1860.09.11.xml | title = How to Vote | publisher = The Staunton Spectator | date = September 11, 1860 | accessdate = August 2, 2011}}</ref> while the ''Vindicator'' ran, e.g., stories reporting on \"unruly\" slaves mutilating themselves to escape being sold.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.pbs.org/wnet/slavery/experience/responses/docs8.html | title = Desperate Negro Woman | publisher = The Staunton Vindicator | year = 1861 | accessdate = August 2, 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn May 23, 1861, shortly after the firing on Fort Sumter began the [[American Civil War]], Virginians voted on whether to ratify [[Virginia in the American Civil War#Secession timeline|articles of secession]] from the Union and join the [[Confederate States]]. The articles were overwhelmingly approved throughout the Commonwealth, even in the majority of the counties that would later become West Virginia. The vote in Staunton was 3300 in favor of secession,{{citation needed|reason=Wikipedia article on West Virginia states most of the region opposed secession|date=January 2018}} with only 6 opposed.<ref>{{cite news|publisher=New York Times|date=June 1, 1861|page=8|title=The Vote for Secession in Virginia}}</ref>  During the war, the town became an important [[Shenandoah Valley]] manufacturing center, a staging area, and a supply depot for the [[Confederate States of America|Confederacy]].\n\nOn June 6, 1864, [[Union (American Civil War)|Union]] Major General [[David Hunter]] arrived<ref>{{cite news|title=From General Hunter, Capture of Staunton, Virginia|work=The Daily Age|date=June 13, 1864|page=1|place=Philadelphia, Pennsylvania}}</ref> with 10,000 troops to cut supply, communication and railway lines useful to the Confederacy. The next day, they destroyed the railroad station, [[warehouse]]s, houses, factories and mills. Union soldiers [[looting|looted]] the stores and warehouses and confiscated supplies.<ref name=ev>{{cite web | url = http://www.encyclopediavirginia.org/Staunton_During_the_Civil_War | title = Staunton During the Civil War | publisher = Encyclopedia Virginia | accessdate = August 17, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Post-bellum Staunton===\nOn July 10, 1902, Staunton became an independent city.<ref name=\"Independent city\">{{cite web\n |url         = http://historical-county.newberry.org/website/Virginia/documents/VA_Individual_County_Chronologies.htm\n |title       = Virginia: Individual County and Independent City Chronologies\n |accessdate  = December 26, 2006\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20060831014231/http://historical-county.newberry.org/website/Virginia/documents/VA_Individual_County_Chronologies.htm\n |archivedate = August 31, 2006\n |df          = mdy-all\n}}</ref>\n[[File:Entrance Stuart-Robertson House Staunton.jpg|thumb|right|175px|Entrance gates, Stuart-Robertson House, Staunton, [[Historic American Buildings Survey]]]]\nIn 1908, Staunton created the [[city manager]] form of government. Charles E. Ashburner was hired by Staunton as the nation's first city manager.\n\n===Western State Hospital===\n{{Main|Western State Hospital (Virginia)}}\nStaunton is also home to the former [[Western State Hospital (Virginia)|Western State Asylum]], a hospital for the mentally ill, which originally began operations in 1828. The hospital was renamed Western State Hospital in 1894.\n\nIn its early days, the facility was a resort-style asylum. It had terraced gardens where patients could plant flowers and take walks, roof walks to provide mountain views, and many architectural details to create an atmosphere that would aid in the healing process.  However, by the mid 19th Century, this utopian model of care had vanished, replaced by overcrowding in the facility and the warehousing of patients.  Techniques such as \"ankle and wrist restraints, physical coercion, and straitjackets\" were used.<ref name=commits />   After the passage of the Eugenical Sterilization Act of 1924 in Virginia,<ref>HOUSE JOINT RESOLUTION NO. 607 (HJ607ER), \"Expressing the General Assembly's regret for Virginia's experience with eugenics\", [http://leg1.state.va.us/cgi-bin/legp504.exe?011+ful+HJ607ER Virginia Legislative Information System]</ref>  patients were forcibly sterilized at Western State<ref>{{cite journal | journal = Augusta Historical Bulletin | author = Amanda Brocato | title = The Campaign for Eugenics in Virginia: The Influence of Dr. J.S. DeJarnette | year = 2008 | pages = 105\u2013117}}</ref> until the law authorizing the practice was repealed in the 1970s.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.hsl.virginia.edu/historical/eugenics/4-influence.cfm | title = Eugenics in Virginia | publisher = Claude Moore Health Sciences Library, University of Virginia | accessdate = July 31, 2011}}</ref>  Later, [[electroshock therapy]] and [[lobotomy|lobotomies]] were practiced at the facility.<ref name=commits />\n\nWhen Western State vacated the property and moved its adult patients to its present site near Interstate 81, the facility was renamed the Staunton Correctional Center and turned into a medium-security men's penitentiary. The prison closed in 2003, and the site was left vacant for several years. In 2005, the state of Virginia gave the original property to the Staunton Industrial Authority.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://leg1.state.va.us/cgi-bin/legp504.exe?051+sum+HB1943 | title = Virginia HB1943/SB1015 | accessdate = July 30, 2011}}</ref>  It is now a condominium complex called The Villages at Staunton.<ref name=commits>{{cite web|url=http://www.readthehook.com/stories/2006/02/02/onarchstaunton.html |title=The HooK: On architecture - Historic treatment: Staunton commits to Western State |publisher=Readthehook.com |date=February 2, 2006 |accessdate=June 14, 2009}}</ref>\n\nA separate complex, The DeJarnette State Sanatoruim, was constructed in 1932 and acted as a location for patients with the ability to pay for their treatment. [http://opacity.us/site163_dejarnette_sanitarium.htm ] Dr. DeJarnette was the superintendent of the sanatorium from its opening until his retirement in 1947.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://ead.lib.virginia.edu/vivaxtf/view?docId=lva/vi00937.xml |title= A Guide to the Records of Western State Hospital, 1825-2000 | accessdate=April 14, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the city has a total area of {{convert|20|sqmi}}, virtually all of which is land.<ref name=\"GR1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/geographies/reference-files/time-series/geo/gazetteer-files.html|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2011-04-23|date=2011-02-12|title=US Gazetteer files: 2010, 2000, and 1990}}</ref> Staunton is located in the [[Shenandoah Valley]] in between the [[Blue Ridge Mountains|Blue Ridge]] and [[Allegheny Mountains]] of the [[Appalachian Mountains]]. It is drained by Lewis Creek. Lewis Creek flows into the Shenandoah River, which flows into the Potomac, and eventually to the Chesapeake Bay.\n\n===Climate===\nThe climate in this area is characterized by hot, humid summers and generally mild to cool winters.  According to the [[K\u00f6ppen Climate Classification]] system, Staunton has a [[humid subtropical climate]], abbreviated \"Cfa\" on climate maps.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.weatherbase.com/weather/weather-summary.php3?s=260844&cityname=Staunton,%20Virginia,%20United%20States%20of%20America&units=|title=Staunton, Virginia K\u00f6ppen Climate Classification (Weatherbase)|publisher=|accessdate=July 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Governance ==\n{| align=\"center\" border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"float:right; margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n|+ '''Presidential Elections Results'''<ref>http://uselectionatlas.org/RESULTS</ref>\n|- bgcolor=lightgrey\n! Year\n! [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n! [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n! [[Third Party (United States)|Third Parties]]\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[United States presidential election in Virginia, 2016|2016]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|45.6% ''5,133''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''47.4%''' ''5,333''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|7.0% ''789''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[United States presidential election in Virginia, 2012|2012]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|47.0% ''5,272''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''51.1%''' ''5,728''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|1.9% ''210''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[United States presidential election in Virginia, 2008|2008]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|48.4% ''5,330''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''50.6%''' ''5,569''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|1.1% ''116''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''[[United States presidential election in Virginia, 2004|2004]]'''\n|  style=\"tex