convert|15|e6lb|t}} of rock in suspension. It is {{convert|30|ft|m}} wide at the top and {{convert|85|ft|m}} at the base; one of the more than 70 natural arches located in the area.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Kentucky Counties|last=Powell|first=Robert|publisher=Kentucky Images|year=1989|location=Lexington, KY|pages=52\u201353}}</ref>\n\n==Communities==\n* [[Clay City, Kentucky|Clay City]]\n* [[Slade, Kentucky|Slade]]\n* [[Stanton, Kentucky|Stanton]] (county seat)\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|United States}}\n* [[National Register of Historic Places listings in Powell County, Kentucky]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.powell.kyschools.us Powell County School District]\n* [http://www.gopoco.org Powell County Tourism]\n\n{{Powell County, Kentucky}}\n{{Eastern Mountain Coal Fields (Kentucky)}}\n{{Kentucky}}\n\n{{Coord|37.83|-83.83|display=title|type:adm2nd_region:US-KY_source:UScensus1990}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Kentucky counties]]\n[[Category:Powell County, Kentucky| ]]\n[[Category:Counties of Appalachia]]\n[[Category:1852 establishments in Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1852]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toCommonwealth (disambiguation)(link changed toCommonwealth (U.S. state)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Powell_County,_Kentucky"}
{"title_page": "Timeline of relief efforts after the 2010 Chile earthquake", "text_new": "{{See also|2010 Chile earthquake}}\n{{update|date=November 2010}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n\nThe '''timeline of relief efforts after they had stupidness the [[2010 Chile earthquake]]''' of 27 February 2010 involves the sequence of events in the days following a highly destructive 8.8 {{M|w}} earthquake with an [[epicentre]] just offshore of the Maule Region, see [[Maule, Chile]].<ref>USGS, [https://earthquake.usgs.gov/earthquakes/recenteqsww/Quakes/us2010tfan.php#details Magnitude 8.8 \u2013 Offshore Maule, Chile \u2013 27 February 2010 06:34:14 UTC] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100410032038/http://earthquake.usgs.gov/earthquakes/recenteqsww/Quakes/us2010tfan.php#details |date=10 April 2010 }} (accessed 1 March 2010)</ref>\n{{TOC right}}\n\n==Timeline of relief efforts==\n\n===27 February===\nChile asks that foreign aid be delayed until Chile can complete an initial survey of affected areas.<ref>The Telegraph (London), [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/southamerica/chile/7336716/Chile-earthquake-nation-in-shock-as-death-toll-climbs.html \"Chile earthquake: nation in shock as death toll climbs\"], Bonnie Malkin, 28 February 2010 (accessed 1 March 2010)</ref>\n\nOn [[Robinson Crusoe Island]], 12-year-old Martina Maturana warned her neighbours and saved them from the tsunami.<ref>Huffington Post, [http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2010/03/04/chilean-girl-saves-her-is_n_485835.html \"Chilean Girl Saves Her Island From Tsunami After Earthquake\"], Erica Liepmann,4 March 201 (accessed 4 March 2010)</ref>\n\nApproximately one hour after the earthquake, teenagers in [[Dichato, Chile]], lounging on the beach observed the sea roll out of the horseshoe shaped bay, and immediately ran through town to warn of an impending tsunami. This moved most of the town's population out of harm's way.<ref>Associated Press, [http://www.boston.com/news/world/latinamerica/articles/2010/03/02/after_quake_giant_wave_swallowed_port_town/ \"Teens helped warn of wave\"], ''2 March 2010'' (accessed 3 March 2010)</ref>\n\nA fisherman from [[Constitucion, Chile|Constitucion]] with his skiff, rescued celebrants of the end of summer on an island on the Maule River, making two trips between the island and the riverbank, before being swamped and killed by the third tsunami wave.<ref>CNN, [http://edition.cnn.com/2010/WORLD/americas/03/08/chile.sacrifice/ \"Chilean fisherman faced tsunami to save others\"], Karl Penhaul, 9 March 201 (accessed 9 March 2010)</ref>\n\nThe first report of a tsunami relayed to the central government in Santiago from the [[Juan Fern\u00e1ndez Islands]].<ref>Time Magazine, [http://www.time.com/time/world/article/0,8599,1969009,00.html?iid=sphere-inline-bottom \"Chile's President: Why Did Tsunami Warnings Fail?\"], Eben Harrell, 2 March 201 (accessed 4 March 2010)</ref>\n\nBy early afternoon, Chilean government helicopters had started delivering relief supplies to [[Dichato]].<ref>Washington Post, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/03/02/AR2010030202959.html?hpid=moreheadlines \"Chile's coastal towns face double whammy of damage from earthquake and seaquake\"], Juan Ferero, 3 March 2010 (accessed 3 March 2010)</ref>\n\nA state of emergency was declared in [[Maule Region]] and [[Biobio Region]].<ref name=riaN-2010-03-01>RIA Novosti, [http://en.rian.ru/world/20100301/158047011.html \"Chile imposes curfew in two quake-hit regions\"], EFE,1 March 2010 (accessed 4 March 2010)</ref>\n\n===28 February===\nChile sent in army forces to the affected areas to aid police to quell looting outbreaks.<ref>Associated Press, [https://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5gftklhBTIA-_BbqbM2NnhvJDhW8QD9E5CV5G0 \"Chile sends army against looters, deaths hit 708\"], Michael Warren, 1 March 2010 (accessed 1 March 2010)</ref> Curfews have been declared to aid in controlling the situation.<ref>Momento 24, [http://momento24.com/en/2010/03/01/chile-curfew-declared-as-death-toll-nears-1000-an-argentine-woman-is-among-the-victims/ \"Chile: Curfew declared as death toll nears 1000, an Argentine woman is among the victims\"], Lat AM, 1 March 2010 (accessed 2 March 2010)</ref> The curfews were declared in [[Maule Region]] and [[Biobio Region]].<ref name=riaN-2010-03-01/>\n\nThe [[M\u00e9decins Sans Fronti\u00e8res]] exploratory team arrived in the Chilean capital of [[Santiago, Chile|Santiago]], from Argentina. It has started assessing needs.<ref>MSF, [http://www.msf.org/msfinternational/invoke.cfm?objectid=191AD7B3-15C5-F00A-25185772617E29F7&component=toolkit.article&method=full_html \"First MSF team in Chile assessing earthquake damage \u2013 more staff en route\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100314012940/http://www.msf.org/msfinternational/invoke.cfm?objectid=191AD7B3-15C5-F00A-25185772617E29F7&component=toolkit.article&method=full_html |date=14 March 2010 }}, 1 March 2010 (accessed 1 March 2010)</ref>\n\n===1 March===\nChile formally requests international aid for earthquake relief efforts.<ref>People's Daily, [http://english.people.com.cn/90001/90777/90856/6905896.html \"UN says Chile makes request for aid\"], Xinhua, 2 March 201 (accessed 2 March 2010)</ref> Over 10,000 Chilean troops have been deployed into the affected area.<ref>Windsor Star, [https://windsorstar.com/news/Military+enforces+curfew+Chile/2631044/story.html \"Military enforces curfew in Chile\"], Aislinn Liang, 2 March 2010 (accessed 2 March 2010)</ref> Chile has requested of Canada to provide a surgical field hospital, generators, and telecom equipment.<ref>CBC News, [https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/chile-asks-canada-for-help-1.869221 \"Chile asks Canada for help\"], 1 March 2010 (accessed 1 March 2010)</ref> Chile has requested of Switzerland to provide first aid supplies, civil engineering experts, and rescue teams.<ref>{{in lang|fr}} TSR, [http://www.tsr.ch/tsr/index.html?siteSect=200002&sid=11848244 \"La Suisse examine quel type d'aide elle pourrait apporter au Chili apr\u00e8s le s\u00e9isme meurtrier de samedi\"], SWISS TXT, 1 March 2010 (accessed 2 March 2010)</ref>\n\nThe [[Santiago Metro]] had resumed partial operation.<ref name=FD-2010-03-04>France-Diplomatie, [http://www.diplomatie.gouv.fr/fr/pays-zones-geo_833/chili_495/france-chili_1120/seisme-au-chili-envoi-une-mission-assistance-04.03.10_80423.html \"S\u00e9isme au Chili : envoi d\u2019une mission d\u2019assistance (4 mars 2010)\"], 4 March 2010 (accessed 4 March 2010)</ref>\n\n[[Los Angeles County]] Fire Department's ''California Task Force 2'' (CA-TF2) started mobilizing for deployment to Chile for earthquake rescue efforts.<ref>Fire Engineering, [http://www.fireengineering.com/index/articles/display/1085017277/articles/fire-engineering/government-2/2010/03/catf2-chile-earthquake.html \"California Task Force 2 Mobilizes to Aid Chilean Earthquake Victims\"], 1 March 2010 (accessed 1 March 2010)</ref>\n\n[[Cuba]] begins to organize a medical brigade of 27 personnel to send to Chile<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.juventudrebelde.cu/internacionales/2010-03-03/destacan-pronto-envio-de-ayuda-medica-cubana-a-chile/ |title= ?|author= |date= |work= |publisher= |accessdate=11 August 2010}}</ref>\n\nJapan announces $3 million in grant aid for Chile. Also announced is 30 million yen in relief supplies from the [[Japan International Cooperation Agency]], consisting of generators, water purifiers, tents and other supplies.<ref>Mainichi Daily News, [http://mdn.mainichi.jp/mdnnews/news/20100302p2g00m0in016000c.html \"Japan to provide $3 mil. in emergency aid to quake-struck Chile\"]{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=no }}, Mainichi Japan, 2 March 2010 (accessed 2 March 2010)</ref><ref name=CRI-2010-03-02>{{in lang|fr}} CRI, [http://french.cri.cn/781/2010/03/02/441s213049.htm \"Le gouvernement chilien intensifie ses op\u00e9rations de secours avec l'aide de la communaut\u00e9 internationale\"], 2 March 2010 (accessed 2 February 2010)</ref>\n\nThe European Union announces $4 million in aid for Chile.<ref name=CRI-2010-03-02/>\n\nChina announces $1 million in aid for Chile.<ref name=CRI-2010-03-02/>\n\nArgentina announces it will deploy a field hospital with 54 health professionals, four power plants and three water treatment plants in government aid. As well, the Argentine business community will give 1/2 million litres of bottled water, and 1800 tonnes of non-perishable food in aid.<ref>Momento 24, [http://momento24.com/en/2010/03/01/argentina-is-the-first-country-to-send-aid-to-chile/ \"Argentina is the first country to send aid to Chile\"], Lat Am, 1 March 2010 (accessed 2 March 2010)</ref>\n\nBrazil announces it will deploy a field hospital, medical equipment and mobile bridging equipment.<ref>{{in lang|fr}} CRI, [http://french.cri.cn/621/2010/03/02/302s213062.htm \"Chili/s\u00e9isme : le Br\u00e9sil fournit des h\u00f4pitaux de campagne et des ponts amovibles\"], Xinhua, 2 March 2010 (accessed 2 March 2010)</ref>\n\nRussia announces it will ship two plane-loads full of warm clothing, basic necessities, tents, and generators.<ref>{{in lang|fr}} Figaro, [http://www.lefigaro.fr/flash-actu/2010/03/02/01011-20100302FILWWW00422-seisme-chili-2-avions-russes-en-renfort.php \"S\u00e9isme/Chili: 2 avions russes en renfort\"], AFP, 2 March 201 (accessed 2 March 2010)</ref>\n\n[[Scotiabank]] announces $250,000 in aid for Chile, and a relief fund would be set up through its bank branches in Canada.<ref>CNW Group, [http://www.newswire.ca/en/releases/archive/March2010/01/c5818.html \"Scotiabank Contributes Cdn $250,000 to Chile Earthquake Relief Effort\"], Joe Konecny, 1 March 2010 (accessed 2 March 2010)</ref>\n\n===2 March===\n79 survivors and 7 bodies were recovered from a collapsed 8 storey apartment building in [[Concepci\u00f3n, Chile|Concepci\u00f3n]].<ref>Xinhua, [http://news.xinhuanet.com/english2010/world/2010-03/03/c_13195100.htm \"Rescuers pull out 79 survivors from collapsed building in Chile\"], 3 March 2010 (accessed 3 March 2010)</ref> About 30% of power has been restored to Concepcion.<ref name=WSJ-2010-03-02>Wall Street Journal, [https://online.wsj.com/article/BT-CO-20100302-715850.html?mod=WSJ_latestheadlines \"Chile Power Firms: Slow Process Restoring Power In Quake Zones\"], Matthew Cowley, 2 March 2010 (accessed 3 March 2010)</ref> [[Constitucion, Chile|Constitucion]] and [[Cauquenes, Chile|Cauquenes]] will not be able to get power restored soon due to tsunami damage, on top of earthquake damage.<ref name=WSJ-2010-03-02/>\n\nOver 14,000 Chilean troops have been deployed to the affected region, along with over 50 airplanes, also helicopters, and boats for relief efforts. 5000 emergency shelters were distributed by Chile.<ref>{{in lang|fr}} Le Devoir, [https://www.ledevoir.com/international/amerique-latine/284224/l-aide-humanitaire-et-militaire-fait-son-chemin-au-chili \"L'aide humanitaire et militaire fait son chemin au Chili\"], M\u00e9lissa Guillemette, 3 March 2010 (accessed 3 March 2010)</ref>\n\nThe port of [[San Antonio, Chile|San Antonio]] has recovered to 60% operational, and the port of [[Valpara\u00edso, Chile|Valpara\u00edso]] is operating at 90%. Initial assessment teams from the [[Chilean Exporters Association]] (ASOEX) have checked out damage to industry.<ref>Perishable Pundit, [http://www.perishablepundit.com/index.php?article=0002363 Update on Chile earthquake impact on fruit supplies\"], 3 March 2010 (accessed 5 March 2010)</ref>\n\nCuban support arrives in Chile and sets up a temporary hospital in [[Rancagua]]<ref name=\"english.people.com.cn\">{{Cite web|url=http://english.people.com.cn/90001/90777/90852/6911842.html |title=? |author= |date= |work= |publisher= |accessdate= }}</ref>\n\n===3 March===\nFull operation returned to [[Comodoro Arturo Merino Ben\u00edtez International Airport]], Santiago's airport.<ref>{{in lang|fr}} Business Travel, [http://www.businesstravel.fr/201003024110/en-voyage/aeroports/aeroport-de-santiago-au-chili-retour-a-la-normale-mercredi.html \"A\u00e9roport de Santiago au Chili: retour \u00e0 la normale mercredi\"], 2 March 2010 (accessed 3 March 2010)</ref>\n\nChilean troops locked down Concepcion to prevent looting.<ref>Time Magazine, [http://www.time.com/time/world/article/0,8599,1969570,00.html \"Quake Response Doesn't Live Up to Chile's Self-Image\"], 'Eben Harrell, 4 March 2010 (accessed 4 March 2010)</ref>\n\nThe port of [[San Antonio, Chile|San Antonio]] was shut down by the earthquake, but had resumed operation at 80% capacity.<ref>Bloomberg News, [https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601086&sid=aW.tGFQaicJs \"Chile\u2019s San Antonio Port Returns to 80% Capacity\"], 'Rodrigo Orihuela, James Attwood, 3 March 2010 (accessed 4 March 2010)</ref>\n\nFirefighters in [[Nuble Province]] are shipping river water in their trucks up into the hills to residents fearful of further tsunamis, who have abandoned their villages, and staying in makeshift camps.<ref>Reuters, [http://uk.reuters.com/article/idUKN03219039._CH_.2420 \"Fearing tsunamis in Chile, hundreds hide in hills\"], Mica Rosenberg, 3 March 2010 (accessed 4 March 2010)</ref>\n\nUN's [[Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs]] (OCHA) has announced that the priority is food, power and water, for relief provisioning.<ref>{{in lang|fr}} Branchez-Vous, [http://matin.branchez-vous.com/nouvelles/2010/03/chili_nourriture_electricite_e.html \"Chili: nourriture, \u00e9lectricit\u00e9 et eau sont les priorit\u00e9s selon OCHA\"]{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=no }}, Olivier Caron, 4 March 2010 (accessed 4 March 2010)</ref>\n\nFrance is sending 1.3 tonnes of aid, and 7 seismologists.<ref>{{in lang|fr}} Figaro, [http://www.lefigaro.fr/flash-actu/2010/03/04/01011-20100304FILWWW00572-chili-la-france-envoie-un-avion-d-aide.php \"Chili: la France envoie un avion d'aide\"], AFP, 4 March 2010 (accessed 4 March 2010)</ref>\n\n===4 March===\nLarge amounts of aid have started to arrive in Chile.<ref name=XH-2010-03-04>Xinhua, [http://news.xinhuanet.com/english2010/world/2010-03/04/c_13197550.htm \"Aid pours into Chile as aftershocks still threaten\"], 4 March 2010 (accessed 4 March 2010)</ref>\n\nChina has shipped $2 million in aid supplies, including, 700 tents, 10000 blankets, 100 portable power generators, 2 water purifiers.<ref name=XH-2010-03-04/>\n\nVenezuela has sent rescue experts, 7.2 tons of food and water, 400 blankets.<ref name=XH-2010-03-04/>\n\nThe first Russian Il-76 cargo plane filled with relief supplies had arrived, carrying 28 tons of tents, diesel generators, pumps, blankets, food.<ref>RIA Novosti, [http://en.rian.ru/russia/20100305/158097559.html \"Russian humanitarian aid arrives in quake-hit Chile\"],  5 March 2010 (accessed 5 March 2010)</ref>\n\nAircrews and maintenance support personnel from Missouri Air National Guard's 139th Airlift Wing are being deployed to Santiago.<ref>News-Leader, [http://www.news-leader.com/article/20100304/BREAKING01/100304039/Air-National-Guard-sending-support-crews-to-Chile \"Air National Guard sending support crews to Chile\"], 4 March 2010 (accessed 4 March 2010)</ref>\n\nThe European Union is sending an assistance mission to Chile. Included on the mission is a number of seismologists, with 27 seismological stations, [[Iridium satellite constellation|Iridium]] satellite communications equipment, dialysis machine, water purifier, and a medical team.<ref name=FD-2010-03-04/>\n\nCroatia donated 500,000 [[Croatian kuna|HRK]] (90,000 USD) to Red Cross.<ref>[http://www.vlada.hr/hr/naslovnica/priopcenja_za_javnost/2010/ozujak/priopcenje_sa_44_sjednice_vlade_rh Priop\u0107enje sa 44. sjednice Vlade RH] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607195244/http://www.vlada.hr/hr/naslovnica/priopcenja_za_javnost/2010/ozujak/priopcenje_sa_44_sjednice_vlade_rh |date=7 June 2011 }}</ref>\n\n''Hyundai/Kia'' announced $200,000 in aid for Chile.<ref>Trading Market, [http://www.tradingmarkets.com/news/stock-alert/kimty_hyundai-kia-to-provide-us-200-000-in-aid-to-quake-stricken-chile-831811.html \"Hyundai, Kia to provide US$200,000 in aid to quake-stricken Chile\"]{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=no }}, COMTEX, 5 March 2010 (accessed 9 March 2010)</ref>\n\nLooting has largely been quelled.<ref name=XH-2010-03-04/> Firefighters in [[Talca]] had started inspecting buildings to see if they were habitable.<ref name=ABC-2010-03-04/> A period of national mourning has been announced.<ref>Strait Times, [http://www.straitstimes.com/BreakingNews/World/Story/STIStory_498246.html \"Chile declares national mourning\"], AFP, 5 March 2010 (accessed 5 March 2010)</ref> Turismo Chile has reported that most tourist attractions survived undamaged through the quake. Tourist officials say that Chile is ready for business, and would like tourism to help the country recover.<ref>The Telegraph (London), [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/travelnews/7370132/Chile-earthquake-appeal-for-tourists-to-return.html \"Chile earthquake: appeal for tourists to return\"], Charles Starmer-Smith, 5 March 2010 (accessed 5 March 2010)</ref>\n\nA reconstruction estimate of 4 years and $30 billion has been released.<ref name=XH-2010-03-04/> An assessment has been made that stated that some coastal towns may be unrecoverable.<ref name=ABC-2010-03-04>ABC News (Australia), [http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2010/03/04/2836941.htm?section=justin \"Chile's coastal villages face uncertain future\"], Sarah Dingle, 4 March 2010 (accessed 4 March 2010)</ref>\n\n===5 March===\nAustralia is preparing an aid flight for Chile, consisting of 150 tents, 1000 field beds, 50 generators.<ref>ABC News (Australia), [http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2010/03/06/2838321.htm?section=justin \"Australian aid plane heads to Chile\"], 5 March 2010 (accessed 5 March 2010)</ref>\n\nIndia has pledged $5 million in aid for Chile.<ref>The Times of India, [http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/India-pledges-5-million-for-Chile-earthquake-relief/articleshow/5646233.cms \"India pledges $5 million for Chile earthquake relief\"], 'IANS, 5 March 2010 (accessed 5 March 2010)</ref>\n\nVietnam has pledged $150,000 in aid for Chile.<ref>Voice of Vietnam, [http://english.vovnews.vn/Home/Vietnam-provides-US150000-to-Chiles-quake-victims/20103/113246.vov \"Vietnam provides US$150,000 to Chile\u2019s quake victims\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100311075131/http://english.vovnews.vn/Home/Vietnam-provides-US150000-to-Chiles-quake-victims/20103/113246.vov |date=11 March 2010 }}, VOV News, 6 March 2010 (accessed 6 March 2010)</ref>\n\nThe United Nations has announced it will provide $10 million in aid.<ref>{{in lang|fr}} Figaro, [http://www.lefigaro.fr/flash-actu/2010/03/05/01011-20100305FILWWW00721-chili-l-onu-envoie-10-m.php \"Chili: l'ONU envoie 10 M$\"], AFP, 5 March 2010 (accessed 5 March 2010)</ref>\n\n$1 million from ''Walmart'' and $500,000 from ''Hewlett Packard'' in aid has been announced.<ref>Weekend Today, [http://www.todayonline.com/BreakingNews/EDC100306-0000043/UN-Secretary-General-arrives-in-Chilean-capital,-Santiago,-promises-support \"UN Secretary-General arrives in Chilean capital, Santiago, promises support\"], AP, 6 March 2010 (accessed 5 March 2010)</ref> ''Anglo American'' announced $10 million in aid for emergency water and power, and reconstruction of homes and schools.<ref>Steel Guru, [http://steelguru.com/news/index/MTM1NTkw/Anglo_American_donates_USD_10_million_to_support_reconstruction_in_Chile.html \"Anglo American donates USD 10 million to support reconstruction in Chile\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20120703031732/http://steelguru.com/news/index/MTM1NTkw/Anglo_American_donates_USD_10_million_to_support_reconstruction_in_Chile.html |date=3 July 2012 }}, 6 March 2010 (accessed 6 March 2010)</ref>\n\nChile reports that 35 nations have responded to specific requests for aid issued by the Chilean government.<ref name=Pulse-2010-03-07/>\n\n===6 March===\nChile has launched a [[vaccination]] campaign against [[tetanus]] and [[hepatitis]]. Over a dozen Chilean military and civilian [[field hospital]]s have been deployed.<ref name=UKPA-2010-03-06>UKPA, [https://www.google.com/hostednews/ukpress/article/ALeqM5iBff_XdP-pA7r-utFKQZ9iV3hxiA \"Foreign hospitals help out Chile\"], 6 March 2010 (accessed 6 March 2010)</ref> The curfew period has been shortened.<ref>ABC News (Australia), [http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2010/03/07/2838751.htm?section=world \"Curfew shortened in devastated Chile\"], AFP', 6 March 2010 (accessed 7 March 2010)</ref> President Michelle Bachelet says that foreign soup kitchens will not be needed in Chile.<ref>ABS-CBN News, [http://www.abs-cbnnews.com/world/03/07/10/viva-chile-nation-rallies-help-quake-victims \"Viva Chile! Nation rallies to help quake victims\"], Carlos Hamann, 7 March 2010 (accessed 8 March 2010)</ref>\n\nA US military field hospital is running in [[Angol, Chile]].<ref name=UKPA-2010-03-06/> Two C-130 cargo aircraft and 50 airmen arrived in Chile to help in relief operations.<ref>DVIDS, [http://www.dvidshub.net/?script=news/news_show.php&id=46265 \"Two C-130 Aircraft Arrive in Chile to Support Earthquake Relief Efforts\"], U.S. Southern Command Public Affairs, 6 March 2010 (accessed 7 March 2010)</ref>\n\nA Peruvian field hospital with 3 ORs and 28 beds is running in [[Concepci\u00f3n, Chile]].<ref name=UKPA-2010-03-06/>\n\nThe second Russian plane-load of 28 tons of aid arrived, consisting of tents, diesel generators, blankets.<ref>Ria Novosti, [http://en.rian.ru/world/20100306/158116202.html \"Second plane with Russian humanitarian aid lands in Chile\"], RIAN, 6 March 201 (accessed 7 March 2010)</ref>\n\nThe first 70 tonnes of food from the [[World Food Program]] has arrived.<ref name=AJ-2010-03-07/> The food consists of high-energy biscuits, capable of feeding 35,000 children.<ref>ReliefWeb, [http://www.reliefweb.int/rw/rwb.nsf/db900SID/MYAI-83B6PT?OpenDocument \"WFP airlifts emergency food to help earthquake victims in Chile\"], WFP, 6 March 2010 (accessed 7 March 2010)</ref>\n\na plane carrying 2 million U.S. dollars worth of relief supplies arrives from China in Santiago<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://english.peopledaily.com.cn/90001/90776/90883/6910676.html |title=? |author= |date= |work= |publisher= |accessdate=}}</ref>\n\nCuba sends additional medical personnel to complement its pre-existing relief force in Rancagua<ref name=\"english.people.com.cn\"/>\n\n===7 March===\nChile has started a three-day period of mourning.<ref name=Pulse-2010-03-07/><ref name=AJ-2010-03-07>Al-Jazeera, [http://english.aljazeera.net/news/americas/2010/03/2010376321669257.html \"Chile mourns earthquake victims\"], 7 March 2010 (accessed 7 March 2010)</ref> Efforts have started to repair the fishing industry.<ref>Fish Update, [http://www.fishupdate.com/news/fullstory.php/aid/13245/Chile_starts_to_rebuild_shattered_fishing_industry.html \"Chile starts to rebuild shattered fishing industry\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100715181000/http://www.fishupdate.com/news/fullstory.php/aid/13245/Chile_starts_to_rebuild_shattered_fishing_industry.html |date=15 July 2010 }}, 8 March 2010 (accessed 9 March 2010)</ref>\n\n[[Geodynamicist]]s, [[geophysicist]]s, [[geodesist]]s, [[seismologist]]s, earthquake engineers are pouring into Chile. At least 25 new seismic stations are to be set up in Maule and Biobio regions. Previously fixed survey sites are being resurveyed to measure movements from the quake and its aftershocks.<ref>Washington Post, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/03/07/AR2010030703020.html?hpid=moreheadlines \"For scientists, Chile becomes the ideal lab for studying seismic activity\"], Juan Forero, 8 March 2010 (accessed 8 March 2010)</ref>\n\nCuba has dispatched 9 more doctors and 12 more tons of aid and medical equipment, adding to its contribution of a medical brigade of 27 doctors and 9 staff that is running a temporary hospital in [[Rancagua, Chile|Rancagua]].<ref>Morning Star, [http://www.morningstaronline.co.uk/index.php/news/content/view/full/87707 Morningstaronline.co.uk] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100311021901/http://www.morningstaronline.co.uk/index.php/news/content/view/full/87707 |date=11 March 2010 }}, 8 March 2010 (accessed 9 March 2010)</ref>\n\n[[Chile helps Chile]] (''Chile ayuda a Chile'') raises $30 billion pesos ($60 million USD).<ref name=Pulse-2010-03-07>The Pulse, [http://www.thepulse.cl/2010/03/07/chile-weekend-brief-march-6th-7th/ \"Chile Weekend Brief: March 6th\u20137th\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100701085640/http://www.thepulse.cl/2010/03/07/chile-weekend-brief-march-6th-7th/ |date=1 July 2010 }}, 'Dan Brewington', 7 March 2010 (accessed 8 March 2010)</ref><ref>News 24, [http://www.news24.com/Content/World/News/1073/e26efc86f571485b9cc6f3688cb2caa5/07-03-2010-09-32/Stars_raise_$57m_for_Chile \"Stars raise $57m for Chile\"], SAPA, 7 March 2010 (accessed 8 March 2010)</ref>\n\n===8 March===\nThe Chilean government has estimated that the cost to rebuild the damaged hospitals will be about $3.6 billion.<ref>Sify News, [http://sify.com/news/rebuilding-quake-destroyed-hospitals-to-cost-chile-3-6-bn-news-international-kdjkEbihbfj.html \"Rebuilding quake-destroyed hospitals to cost Chile $3.6 bn\"], EFE, 9 March 2010 (accessed 9 March 2010)</ref>\n\nThe [[Ministry of Defense (Argentina)|Argentine Ministry of Defense]] announced that, after 9 flights, the [[Argentine Air Force Mobile Field Hospital]] at Curico is already operational <ref>[http://www.mindef.gov.ar/info.asp?Id=1376 El hopital de Campa\u00f1a Argentino instalado en Chile ya est\u00e1 en functionamiento] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928113820/http://www.mindef.gov.ar/info.asp?Id=1376 |date=28 September 2011 }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Potash Corporation of Saskatchewan]] Inc. has donated $300,000.<ref>Global News, [http://news.globaltv.com/PotashCorp+makes+donation+Chile/2662894/story.html \"PotashCorp makes donation to Chile\"], Sarah Richter, 9 March 2010 (accessed 10 March 2010)</ref>\n\nWaste and recycling experts say that Constitucion's wreckage can be reused, and that proceeds from the sales of the rubble can help rebuilding efforts.<ref>AFP, [https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5ijZUgPemE4FgWV6YLWGbzZ6p2zUQ \"Recyclers see gold in Chile quake debris\"], Carlos Hamann, 9 March 2010 (accessed 10 March 2010)</ref>\n\n===9 March===\n[[Queensland, Australia]] has donated $500,000 to Chile.<ref>news.com.au, [http://www.news.com.au/breaking-news/state-donates-half-a-million-dollars-to-devastated-chile/story-e6frfku0-1225838940897 \"State donates half a million dollars to devastated Chile\"], AAP, 10 March 2010 (accessed 10 March 2010)</ref>\n\nA CMAT medical team was rerouted from Chile to Haiti after it was determined that there was a lesser need in Chile.<ref>Edmonton Sun, [http://www.edmontonsun.com/news/edmonton/2010/03/10/13186181.html \"Local ER docs rerouted from Chile to Haiti\"], Kristy Brownlee, 10 March 2010 (accessed 11 March 2010)</ref>\n\n===10 March===\nAn estimated $7 billion will be disbursed for insurance claims due to the earthquake.<ref>Sify, [http://sify.com/news/chile-earthquake-cost-insurers-up-to-7-bn-news-international-kdlkOfbbbej.html \"Chile earthquake cost insurers up to $7 bn\"], EFE, 11 March 201 (accessed 11 March 2010)</ref>\n\nThe US Congress has passed a bill to better allow for donations for Chilean quake relief.<ref>Focus, [http://www.focus-fen.net/index.php?id=n212738 \"US House approves Chile aid bill\"], AFP, 11 March 2010 (accessed 11 March 2010)</ref>\n\n===14 March===\nMore than 1600 people have been arrested for looting since the earthquake.<ref>Edmonton Journal, [https://edmontonjournal.com/news/Earthquake+looters+arrested/2681397/story.html \"Earthquake looters arrested\"], CanWest News Service, 14 March 2010 (accessed 14 March 2010)</ref>\n\n===16 March===\nAn estimate that 70,000 emergency shelters are needed was released.<ref>{{in lang|fr}} Figaro, [http://www.lefigaro.fr/flash-actu/2010/03/17/97001-20100317FILWWW00683-chili-70000-logements-necessaires.php \"Chili: 70.000 logements n\u00e9cessaires\"], AFP, 17 March 201. (accessed 20 March 2010)</ref>\n\n===19 March===\nThe Chilean government unveiled a $110 million recovery plan for the central regions.<ref>Channel News Asia, [http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/afp_world/view/1044806/1/.html \"Chile unveils US$110m reconstruction plan\"], AFP, 20 March 2010 (accessed 20 March 2010)</ref>\n\n===20 March===\nA geomapping cruise has been announced by the US NSF, to map the zone ruptured by the quake, and compare it to previous surveys of the seafloor of the zone.<ref>DNA India, [http://www.dnaindia.com/scitech/report_scientists-to-map-chile-earthquake-site-to-capture-fresh-data_1361326 \"Scientists to map Chile earthquake site to capture fresh data\"], ANI, 20 March 2010 (accessed 27 March 2010)</ref> The survey will use the ship ''Melville'', already on site, when the quake struck, and last eight days.<ref>UPI, [http://www.upi.com/Science_News/2010/03/23/Scientists-study-Chilean-earthquake/UPI-63121269375343/ \"Scientists study Chilean earthquake\"], 23 March 2010 (accessed 27 March 2010)</ref>\n\n===26 March===\nA charity tennis event, \"[[Champions for Chile]]\", has been announced for Saturday 3 April 2010. It would be held in [[Key Biscayne, Florida]], and be held in conjunction with the [[ATP Miami Masters]] of Sunday 4 April 2010. Among the players that would play are [[Andy Roddick]], [[Fernando Gonz\u00e1lez]], [[Gustavo Kuerten]] and [[Jim Courier]]. It is similar to the [[Hit for Haiti]] events for [[2010 Haiti earthquake]] relief. Proceeds would go to Hogar de Christo's Chilean earthquake relief.<ref>Times of India, [http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/tennis/top-stories/Roddick-signs-up-for-Chile-quake-relief-match/articleshow/5733176.cms \"Roddick signs up for Chile quake relief match\"], 'AFP', 27 March 2010 (accessed 30 March 2010)</ref><ref>CBC News, [http://stats.cbc.ca/tennis/story.asp?i=20100327180658230000101&ref=hea&tm=&src= \"Doubles for Chile relief planned at Key Biscayne\"], 27 March 2010 (accessed 30 March 2010)</ref>\n\n===5 April===\n400,000 students are to return to class in the affected region on 12 April.<ref>Latin American Herald Tribune, [http://www.laht.com/article.asp?ArticleId=354720&CategoryId=14094 \"400,000 Chilean Students Heading Back to School\"], 6 April 2010 (accessed 6 April 2010)</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[2010 Chile earthquake]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{2010 Chile earthquake}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Timeline Of Relief Efforts After The 2010 Chile Earthquake}}\n[[Category:2010 Chile earthquake]]\n", "text_old": "{{See also|2010 Chile earthquake}}\n{{update|date=November 2010}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n\nThe '''timeline of relief efforts after the [[2010 Chile earthquake]]''' of 27 February 2010 involves the sequence of events in the days following a highly destructive 8.8 {{M|w}} earthquake with an [[epicentre]] just offshore of the Maule Region, see [[Maule, Chile]].<ref>USGS, [https://earthquake.usgs.gov/earthquakes/recenteqsww/Quakes/us2010tfan.php#details Magnitude 8.8 \u2013 Offshore Maule, Chile \u2013 27 February 2010 06:34:14 UTC] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100410032038/http://earthquake.usgs.gov/earthquakes/recenteqsww/Quakes/us2010tfan.php#details |date=10 April 2010 }} (accessed 1 March 2010)</ref>\n{{TOC right}}\n\n==Timeline of relief efforts==\n\n===27 February===\nChile asks that foreign aid be delayed until Chile can complete an initial survey of affected areas.<ref>The Telegraph (London), [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/southamerica/chile/7336716/Chile-earthquake-nation-in-shock-as-death-toll-climbs.html \"Chile earthquake: nation in shock as death toll climbs\"], Bonnie Malkin, 28 February 2010 (accessed 1 March 2010)</ref>\n\nOn [[Robinson Crusoe Island]], 12-year-old Martina Maturana warned her neighbours and saved them from the tsunami.<ref>Huffington Post, [http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2010/03/04/chilean-girl-saves-her-is_n_485835.html \"Chilean Girl Saves Her Island From Tsunami After Earthquake\"], Erica Liepmann,4 March 201 (accessed 4 March 2010)</ref>\n\nApproximately one hour after the earthquake, teenagers in [[Dichato, Chile]], lounging on the beach observed the sea roll out of the horseshoe shaped bay, and immediately ran through town to warn of an impending tsunami. This moved most of the town's population out of harm's way.<ref>Associated Press, [http://www.boston.com/news/world/latinamerica/articles/2010/03/02/after_quake_giant_wave_swallowed_port_town/ \"Teens helped warn of wave\"], ''2 March 2010'' (accessed 3 March 2010)</ref>\n\nA fisherman from [[Constitucion, Chile|Constitucion]] with his skiff, rescued celebrants of the end of summer on an island on the Maule River, making two trips between the island and the riverbank, before being swamped and killed by the third tsunami wave.<ref>CNN, [http://edition.cnn.com/2010/WORLD/americas/03/08/chile.sacrifice/ \"Chilean fisherman faced tsunami to save others\"], Karl Penhaul, 9 March 201 (accessed 9 March 2010)</ref>\n\nThe first report of a tsunami relayed to the central government in Santiago from the [[Juan Fern\u00e1ndez Islands]].<ref>Time Magazine, [http://www.time.com/time/world/article/0,8599,1969009,00.html?iid=sphere-inline-bottom \"Chile's President: Why Did Tsunami Warnings Fail?\"], Eben Harrell, 2 March 201 (accessed 4 March 2010)</ref>\n\nBy early afternoon, Chilean government helicopters had started delivering relief supplies to [[Dichato]].<ref>Washington Post, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/03/02/AR2010030202959.html?hpid=moreheadlines \"Chile's coastal towns face double whammy of damage from earthquake and seaquake\"], Juan Ferero, 3 March 2010 (accessed 3 March 2010)</ref>\n\nA state of emergency was declared in [[Maule Region]] and [[Biobio Region]].<ref name=riaN-2010-03-01>RIA Novosti, [http://en.rian.ru/world/20100301/158047011.html \"Chile imposes curfew in two quake-hit regions\"], EFE,1 March 2010 (accessed 4 March 2010)</ref>\n\n===28 February===\nChile sent in army forces to the affected areas to aid police to quell looting outbreaks.<ref>Associated Press, [https://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5gftklhBTIA-_BbqbM2NnhvJDhW8QD9E5CV5G0 \"Chile sends army against looters, deaths hit 708\"], Michael Warren, 1 March 2010 (accessed 1 March 2010)</ref> Curfews have been declared to aid in controlling the situation.<ref>Momento 24, [http://momento24.com/en/2010/03/01/chile-curfew-declared-as-death-toll-nears-1000-an-argentine-woman-is-among-the-victims/ \"Chile: Curfew declared as death toll nears 1000, an Argentine woman is among the victims\"], Lat AM, 1 March 2010 (accessed 2 March 2010)</ref> The curfews were declared in [[Maule Region]] and [[Biobio Region]].<ref name=riaN-2010-03-01/>\n\nThe [[M\u00e9decins Sans Fronti\u00e8res]] exploratory team arrived in the Chilean capital of [[Santiago, Chile|Santiago]], from Argentina. It has started assessing needs.<ref>MSF, [http://www.msf.org/msfinternational/invoke.cfm?objectid=191AD7B3-15C5-F00A-25185772617E29F7&component=toolkit.article&method=full_html \"First MSF team in Chile assessing earthquake damage \u2013 more staff en route\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100314012940/http://www.msf.org/msfinternational/invoke.cfm?objectid=191AD7B3-15C5-F00A-25185772617E29F7&component=toolkit.article&method=full_html |date=14 March 2010 }}, 1 March 2010 (accessed 1 March 2010)</ref>\n\n===1 March===\nChile formally requests international aid for earthquake relief efforts.<ref>People's Daily, [http://english.people.com.cn/90001/90777/90856/6905896.html \"UN says Chile makes request for aid\"], Xinhua, 2 March 201 (accessed 2 March 2010)</ref> Over 10,000 Chilean troops have been deployed into the affected area.<ref>Windsor Star, [https://windsorstar.com/news/Military+enforces+curfew+Chile/2631044/story.html \"Military enforces curfew in Chile\"], Aislinn Liang, 2 March 2010 (accessed 2 March 2010)</ref> Chile has requested of Canada to provide a surgical field hospital, generators, and telecom equipment.<ref>CBC News, [https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/chile-asks-canada-for-help-1.869221 \"Chile asks Canada for help\"], 1 March 2010 (accessed 1 March 2010)</ref> Chile has requested of Switzerland to provide first aid supplies, civil engineering experts, and rescue teams.<ref>{{in lang|fr}} TSR, [http://www.tsr.ch/tsr/index.html?siteSect=200002&sid=11848244 \"La Suisse examine quel type d'aide elle pourrait apporter au Chili apr\u00e8s le s\u00e9isme meurtrier de samedi\"], SWISS TXT, 1 March 2010 (accessed 2 March 2010)</ref>\n\nThe [[Santiago Metro]] had resumed partial operation.<ref name=FD-2010-03-04>France-Diplomatie, [http://www.diplomatie.gouv.fr/fr/pays-zones-geo_833/chili_495/france-chili_1120/seisme-au-chili-envoi-une-mission-assistance-04.03.10_80423.html \"S\u00e9isme au Chili : envoi d\u2019une mission d\u2019assistance (4 mars 2010)\"], 4 March 2010 (accessed 4 March 2010)</ref>\n\n[[Los Angeles County]] Fire Department's ''California Task Force 2'' (CA-TF2) started mobilizing for deployment to Chile for earthquake rescue efforts.<ref>Fire Engineering, [http://www.fireengineering.com/index/articles/display/1085017277/articles/fire-engineering/government-2/2010/03/catf2-chile-earthquake.html \"California Task Force 2 Mobilizes to Aid Chilean Earthquake Victims\"], 1 March 2010 (accessed 1 March 2010)</ref>\n\n[[Cuba]] begins to organize a medical brigade of 27 personnel to send to Chile<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.juventudrebelde.cu/internacionales/2010-03-03/destacan-pronto-envio-de-ayuda-medica-cubana-a-chile/ |title= ?|author= |date= |work= |publisher= |accessdate=11 August 2010}}</ref>\n\nJapan announces $3 million in grant aid for Chile. Also announced is 30 million yen in relief supplies from the [[Japan International Cooperation Agency]], consisting of generators, water purifiers, tents and other supplies.<ref>Mainichi Daily News, [http://mdn.mainichi.jp/mdnnews/news/20100302p2g00m0in016000c.html \"Japan to provide $3 mil. in emergency aid to quake-struck Chile\"]{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=no }}, Mainichi Japan, 2 March 2010 (accessed 2 March 2010)</ref><ref name=CRI-2010-03-02>{{in lang|fr}} CRI, [http://french.cri.cn/781/2010/03/02/441s213049.htm \"Le gouvernement chilien intensifie ses op\u00e9rations de secours avec l'aide de la communaut\u00e9 internationale\"], 2 March 2010 (accessed 2 February 2010)</ref>\n\nThe European Union announces $4 million in aid for Chile.<ref name=CRI-2010-03-02/>\n\nChina announces $1 million in aid for Chile.<ref name=CRI-2010-03-02/>\n\nArgentina announces it will deploy a field hospital with 54 health professionals, four power plants and three water treatment plants in government aid. As well, the Argentine business community will give 1/2 million litres of bottled water, and 1800 tonnes of non-perishable food in aid.<ref>Momento 24, [http://momento24.com/en/2010/03/01/argentina-is-the-first-country-to-send-aid-to-chile/ \"Argentina is the first country to send aid to Chile\"], Lat Am, 1 March 2010 (accessed 2 March 2010)</ref>\n\nBrazil announces it will deploy a field hospital, medical equipment and mobile bridging equipment.<ref>{{in lang|fr}} CRI, [http://french.cri.cn/621/2010/03/02/302s213062.htm \"Chili/s\u00e9isme : le Br\u00e9sil fournit des h\u00f4pitaux de campagne et des ponts amovibles\"], Xinhua, 2 March 2010 (accessed 2 March 2010)</ref>\n\nRussia announces it will ship two plane-loads full of warm clothing, basic necessities, tents, and generators.<ref>{{in lang|fr}} Figaro, [http://www.lefigaro.fr/flash-actu/2010/03/02/01011-20100302FILWWW00422-seisme-chili-2-avions-russes-en-renfort.php \"S\u00e9isme/Chili: 2 avions russes en renfort\"], AFP, 2 March 201 (accessed 2 March 2010)</ref>\n\n[[Scotiabank]] announces $250,000 in aid for Chile, and a relief fund would be set up through its bank branches in Canada.<ref>CNW Group, [http://www.newswire.ca/en/releases/archive/March2010/01/c5818.html \"Scotiabank Contributes Cdn $250,000 to Chile Earthquake Relief Effort\"], Joe Konecny, 1 March 2010 (accessed 2 March 2010)</ref>\n\n===2 March===\n79 survivors and 7 bodies were recovered from a collapsed 8 storey apartment building in [[Concepci\u00f3n, Chile|Concepci\u00f3n]].<ref>Xinhua, [http://news.xinhuanet.com/english2010/world/2010-03/03/c_13195100.htm \"Rescuers pull out 79 survivors from collapsed building in Chile\"], 3 March 2010 (accessed 3 March 2010)</ref> About 30% of power has been restored to Concepcion.<ref name=WSJ-2010-03-02>Wall Street Journal, [https://online.wsj.com/article/BT-CO-20100302-715850.html?mod=WSJ_latestheadlines \"Chile Power Firms: Slow Process Restoring Power In Quake Zones\"], Matthew Cowley, 2 March 2010 (accessed 3 March 2010)</ref> [[Constitucion, Chile|Constitucion]] and [[Cauquenes, Chile|Cauquenes]] will not be able to get power restored soon due to tsunami damage, on top of earthquake damage.<ref name=WSJ-2010-03-02/>\n\nOver 14,000 Chilean troops have been deployed to the affected region, along with over 50 airplanes, also helicopters, and boats for relief efforts. 5000 emergency shelters were distributed by Chile.<ref>{{in lang|fr}} Le Devoir, [https://www.ledevoir.com/international/amerique-latine/284224/l-aide-humanitaire-et-militaire-fait-son-chemin-au-chili \"L'aide humanitaire et militaire fait son chemin au Chili\"], M\u00e9lissa Guillemette, 3 March 2010 (accessed 3 March 2010)</ref>\n\nThe port of [[San Antonio, Chile|San Antonio]] has recovered to 60% operational, and the port of [[Valpara\u00edso, Chile|Valpara\u00edso]] is operating at 90%. Initial assessment teams from the [[Chilean Exporters Association]] (ASOEX) have checked out damage to industry.<ref>Perishable Pundit, [http://www.perishablepundit.com/index.php?article=0002363 Update on Chile earthquake impact on fruit supplies\"], 3 March 2010 (accessed 5 March 2010)</ref>\n\nCuban support arrives in Chile and sets up a temporary hospital in [[Rancagua]]<ref name=\"english.people.com.cn\">{{Cite web|url=http://english.people.com.cn/90001/90777/90852/6911842.html |title=? |author= |date= |work= |publisher= |accessdate= }}</ref>\n\n===3 March===\nFull operation returned to [[Comodoro Arturo Merino Ben\u00edtez International Airport]], Santiago's airport.<ref>{{in lang|fr}} Business Travel, [http://www.businesstravel.fr/201003024110/en-voyage/aeroports/aeroport-de-santiago-au-chili-retour-a-la-normale-mercredi.html \"A\u00e9roport de Santiago au Chili: retour \u00e0 la normale mercredi\"], 2 March 2010 (accessed 3 March 2010)</ref>\n\nChilean troops locked down Concepcion to prevent looting.<ref>Time Magazine, [http://www.time.com/time/world/article/0,8599,1969570,00.html \"Quake Response Doesn't Live Up to Chile's Self-Image\"], 'Eben Harrell, 4 March 2010 (accessed 4 March 2010)</ref>\n\nThe port of [[San Antonio, Chile|San Antonio]] was shut down by the earthquake, but had resumed operation at 80% capacity.<ref>Bloomberg News, [https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601086&sid=aW.tGFQaicJs \"Chile\u2019s San Antonio Port Returns to 80% Capacity\"], 'Rodrigo Orihuela, James Attwood, 3 March 2010 (accessed 4 March 2010)</ref>\n\nFirefighters in [[Nuble Province]] are shipping river water in their trucks up into the hills to residents fearful of further tsunamis, who have abandoned their villages, and staying in makeshift camps.<ref>Reuters, [http://uk.reuters.com/article/idUKN03219039._CH_.2420 \"Fearing tsunamis in Chile, hundreds hide in hills\"], Mica Rosenberg, 3 March 2010 (accessed 4 March 2010)</ref>\n\nUN's [[Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs]] (OCHA) has announced that the priority is food, power and water, for relief provisioning.<ref>{{in lang|fr}} Branchez-Vous, [http://matin.branchez-vous.com/nouvelles/2010/03/chili_nourriture_electricite_e.html \"Chili: nourriture, \u00e9lectricit\u00e9 et eau sont les priorit\u00e9s selon OCHA\"]{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=no }}, Olivier Caron, 4 March 2010 (accessed 4 March 2010)</ref>\n\nFrance is sending 1.3 tonnes of aid, and 7 seismologists.<ref>{{in lang|fr}} Figaro, [http://www.lefigaro.fr/flash-actu/2010/03/04/01011-20100304FILWWW00572-chili-la-france-envoie-un-avion-d-aide.php \"Chili: la France envoie un avion d'aide\"], AFP, 4 March 2010 (accessed 4 March 2010)</ref>\n\n===4 March===\nLarge amounts of aid have started to arrive in Chile.<ref name=XH-2010-03-04>Xinhua, [http://news.xinhuanet.com/english2010/world/2010-03/04/c_13197550.htm \"Aid pours into Chile as aftershocks still threaten\"], 4 March 2010 (accessed 4 March 2010)</ref>\n\nChina has shipped $2 million in aid supplies, including, 700 tents, 10000 blankets, 100 portable power generators, 2 water purifiers.<ref name=XH-2010-03-04/>\n\nVenezuela has sent rescue experts, 7.2 tons of food and water, 400 blankets.<ref name=XH-2010-03-04/>\n\nThe first Russian Il-76 cargo plane filled with relief supplies had arrived, carrying 28 tons of tents, diesel generators, pumps, blankets, food.<ref>RIA Novosti, [http://en.rian.ru/russia/20100305/158097559.html \"Russian humanitarian aid arrives in quake-hit Chile\"],  5 March 2010 (accessed 5 March 2010)</ref>\n\nAircrews and maintenance support personnel from Missouri Air National Guard's 139th Airlift Wing are being deployed to Santiago.<ref>News-Leader, [http://www.news-leader.com/article/20100304/BREAKING01/100304039/Air-National-Guard-sending-support-crews-to-Chile \"Air National Guard sending support crews to Chile\"], 4 March 2010 (accessed 4 March 2010)</ref>\n\nThe European Union is sending an assistance mission to Chile. Included on the mission is a number of seismologists, with 27 seismological stations, [[Iridium satellite constellation|Iridium]] satellite communications equipment, dialysis machine, water purifier, and a medical team.<ref name=FD-2010-03-04/>\n\nCroatia donated 500,000 [[Croatian kuna|HRK]] (90,000 USD) to Red Cross.<ref>[http://www.vlada.hr/hr/naslovnica/priopcenja_za_javnost/2010/ozujak/priopcenje_sa_44_sjednice_vlade_rh Priop\u0107enje sa 44. sjednice Vlade RH] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607195244/http://www.vlada.hr/hr/naslovnica/priopcenja_za_javnost/2010/ozujak/priopcenje_sa_44_sjednice_vlade_rh |date=7 June 2011 }}</ref>\n\n''Hyundai/Kia'' announced $200,000 in aid for Chile.<ref>Trading Market, [http://www.tradingmarkets.com/news/stock-alert/kimty_hyundai-kia-to-provide-us-200-000-in-aid-to-quake-stricken-chile-831811.html \"Hyundai, Kia to provide US$200,000 in aid to quake-stricken Chile\"]{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=no }}, COMTEX, 5 March 2010 (accessed 9 March 2010)</ref>\n\nLooting has largely been quelled.<ref name=XH-2010-03-04/> Firefighters in [[Talca]] had started inspecting buildings to see if they were habitable.<ref name=ABC-2010-03-04/> A period of national mourning has been announced.<ref>Strait Times, [http://www.straitstimes.com/BreakingNews/World/Story/STIStory_498246.html \"Chile declares national mourning\"], AFP, 5 March 2010 (accessed 5 March 2010)</ref> Turismo Chile has reported that most tourist attractions survived undamaged through the quake. Tourist officials say that Chile is ready for business, and would like tourism to help the country recover.<ref>The Telegraph (London), [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/travelnews/7370132/Chile-earthquake-appeal-for-tourists-to-return.html \"Chile earthquake: appeal for tourists to return\"], Charles Starmer-Smith, 5 March 2010 (accessed 5 March 2010)</ref>\n\nA reconstruction estimate of 4 years and $30 billion has been released.<ref name=XH-2010-03-04/> An assessment has been made that stated that some coastal towns may be unrecoverable.<ref name=ABC-2010-03-04>ABC News (Australia), [http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2010/03/04/2836941.htm?section=justin \"Chile's coastal villages face uncertain future\"], Sarah Dingle, 4 March 2010 (accessed 4 March 2010)</ref>\n\n===5 March===\nAustralia is preparing an aid flight for Chile, consisting of 150 tents, 1000 field beds, 50 generators.<ref>ABC News (Australia), [http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2010/03/06/2838321.htm?section=justin \"Australian aid plane heads to Chile\"], 5 March 2010 (accessed 5 March 2010)</ref>\n\nIndia has pledged $5 million in aid for Chile.<ref>The Times of India, [http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/India-pledges-5-million-for-Chile-earthquake-relief/articleshow/5646233.cms \"India pledges $5 million for Chile earthquake relief\"], 'IANS, 5 March 2010 (accessed 5 March 2010)</ref>\n\nVietnam has pledged $150,000 in aid for Chile.<ref>Voice of Vietnam, [http://english.vovnews.vn/Home/Vietnam-provides-US150000-to-Chiles-quake-victims/20103/113246.vov \"Vietnam provides US$150,000 to Chile\u2019s quake victims\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100311075131/http://english.vovnews.vn/Home/Vietnam-provides-US150000-to-Chiles-quake-victims/20103/113246.vov |date=11 March 2010 }}, VOV News, 6 March 2010 (accessed 6 March 2010)</ref>\n\nThe United Nations has announced it will provide $10 million in aid.<ref>{{in lang|fr}} Figaro, [http://www.lefigaro.fr/flash-actu/2010/03/05/01011-20100305FILWWW00721-chili-l-onu-envoie-10-m.php \"Chili: l'ONU envoie 10 M$\"], AFP, 5 March 2010 (accessed 5 March 2010)</ref>\n\n$1 million from ''Walmart'' and $500,000 from ''Hewlett Packard'' in aid has been announced.<ref>Weekend Today, [http://www.todayonline.com/BreakingNews/EDC100306-0000043/UN-Secretary-General-arrives-in-Chilean-capital,-Santiago,-promises-support \"UN Secretary-General arrives in Chilean capital, Santiago, promises support\"], AP, 6 March 2010 (accessed 5 March 2010)</ref> ''Anglo American'' announced $10 million in aid for emergency water and power, and reconstruction of homes and schools.<ref>Steel Guru, [http://steelguru.com/news/index/MTM1NTkw/Anglo_American_donates_USD_10_million_to_support_reconstruction_in_Chile.html \"Anglo American donates USD 10 million to support reconstruction in Chile\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20120703031732/http://steelguru.com/news/index/MTM1NTkw/Anglo_American_donates_USD_10_million_to_support_reconstruction_in_Chile.html |date=3 July 2012 }}, 6 March 2010 (accessed 6 March 2010)</ref>\n\nChile reports that 35 nations have responded to specific requests for aid issued by the Chilean government.<ref name=Pulse-2010-03-07/>\n\n===6 March===\nChile has launched a [[vaccination]] campaign against [[tetanus]] and [[hepatitis]]. Over a dozen Chilean military and civilian [[field hospital]]s have been deployed.<ref name=UKPA-2010-03-06>UKPA, [https://www.google.com/hostednews/ukpress/article/ALeqM5iBff_XdP-pA7r-utFKQZ9iV3hxiA \"Foreign hospitals help out Chile\"], 6 March 2010 (accessed 6 March 2010)</ref> The curfew period has been shortened.<ref>ABC News (Australia), [http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2010/03/07/2838751.htm?section=world \"Curfew shortened in devastated Chile\"], AFP', 6 March 2010 (accessed 7 March 2010)</ref> President Michelle Bachelet says that foreign soup kitchens will not be needed in Chile.<ref>ABS-CBN News, [http://www.abs-cbnnews.com/world/03/07/10/viva-chile-nation-rallies-help-quake-victims \"Viva Chile! Nation rallies to help quake victims\"], Carlos Hamann, 7 March 2010 (accessed 8 March 2010)</ref>\n\nA US military field hospital is running in [[Angol, Chile]].<ref name=UKPA-2010-03-06/> Two C-130 cargo aircraft and 50 airmen arrived in Chile to help in relief operations.<ref>DVIDS, [http://www.dvidshub.net/?script=news/news_show.php&id=46265 \"Two C-130 Aircraft Arrive in Chile to Support Earthquake Relief Efforts\"], U.S. Southern Command Public Affairs, 6 March 2010 (accessed 7 March 2010)</ref>\n\nA Peruvian field hospital with 3 ORs and 28 beds is running in [[Concepci\u00f3n, Chile]].<ref name=UKPA-2010-03-06/>\n\nThe second Russian plane-load of 28 tons of aid arrived, consisting of tents, diesel generators, blankets.<ref>Ria Novosti, [http://en.rian.ru/world/20100306/158116202.html \"Second plane with Russian humanitarian aid lands in Chile\"], RIAN, 6 March 201 (accessed 7 March 2010)</ref>\n\nThe first 70 tonnes of food from the [[World Food Program]] has arrived.<ref name=AJ-2010-03-07/> The food consists of high-energy biscuits, capable of feeding 35,000 children.<ref>ReliefWeb, [http://www.reliefweb.int/rw/rwb.nsf/db900SID/MYAI-83B6PT?OpenDocument \"WFP airlifts emergency food to help earthquake victims in Chile\"], WFP, 6 March 2010 (accessed 7 March 2010)</ref>\n\na plane carrying 2 million U.S. dollars worth of relief supplies arrives from China in Santiago<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://english.peopledaily.com.cn/90001/90776/90883/6910676.html |title=? |author= |date= |work= |publisher= |accessdate=}}</ref>\n\nCuba sends additional medical personnel to complement its pre-existing relief force in Rancagua<ref name=\"english.people.com.cn\"/>\n\n===7 March===\nChile has started a three-day period of mourning.<ref name=Pulse-2010-03-07/><ref name=AJ-2010-03-07>Al-Jazeera, [http://english.aljazeera.net/news/americas/2010/03/2010376321669257.html \"Chile mourns earthquake victims\"], 7 March 2010 (accessed 7 March 2010)</ref> Efforts have started to repair the fishing industry.<ref>Fish Update, [http://www.fishupdate.com/news/fullstory.php/aid/13245/Chile_starts_to_rebuild_shattered_fishing_industry.html \"Chile starts to rebuild shattered fishing industry\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100715181000/http://www.fishupdate.com/news/fullstory.php/aid/13245/Chile_starts_to_rebuild_shattered_fishing_industry.html |date=15 July 2010 }}, 8 March 2010 (accessed 9 March 2010)</ref>\n\n[[Geodynamicist]]s, [[geophysicist]]s, [[geodesist]]s, [[seismologist]]s, earthquake engineers are pouring into Chile. At least 25 new seismic stations are to be set up in Maule and Biobio regions. Previously fixed survey sites are being resurveyed to measure movements from the quake and its aftershocks.<ref>Washington Post, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/03/07/AR2010030703020.html?hpid=moreheadlines \"For scientists, Chile becomes the ideal lab for studying seismic activity\"], Juan Forero, 8 March 2010 (accessed 8 March 2010)</ref>\n\nCuba has dispatched 9 more doctors and 12 more tons of aid and medical equipment, adding to its contribution of a medical brigade of 27 doctors and 9 staff that is running a temporary hospital in [[Rancagua, Chile|Rancagua]].<ref>Morning Star, [http://www.morningstaronline.co.uk/index.php/news/content/view/full/87707 Morningstaronline.co.uk] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100311021901/http://www.morningstaronline.co.uk/index.php/news/content/view/full/87707 |date=11 March 2010 }}, 8 March 2010 (accessed 9 March 2010)</ref>\n\n[[Chile helps Chile]] (''Chile ayuda a Chile'') raises $30 billion pesos ($60 million USD).<ref name=Pulse-2010-03-07>The Pulse, [http://www.thepulse.cl/2010/03/07/chile-weekend-brief-march-6th-7th/ \"Chile Weekend Brief: March 6th\u20137th\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100701085640/http://www.thepulse.cl/2010/03/07/chile-weekend-brief-march-6th-7th/ |date=1 July 2010 }}, 'Dan Brewington', 7 March 2010 (accessed 8 March 2010)</ref><ref>News 24, [http://www.news24.com/Content/World/News/1073/e26efc86f571485b9cc6f3688cb2caa5/07-03-2010-09-32/Stars_raise_$57m_for_Chile \"Stars raise $57m for Chile\"], SAPA, 7 March 2010 (accessed 8 March 2010)</ref>\n\n===8 March===\nThe Chilean government has estimated that the cost to rebuild the damaged hospitals will be about $3.6 billion.<ref>Sify News, [http://sify.com/news/rebuilding-quake-destroyed-hospitals-to-cost-chile-3-6-bn-news-international-kdjkEbihbfj.html \"Rebuilding quake-destroyed hospitals to cost Chile $3.6 bn\"], EFE, 9 March 2010 (accessed 9 March 2010)</ref>\n\nThe [[Ministry of Defense (Argentina)|Argentine Ministry of Defense]] announced that, after 9 flights, the [[Argentine Air Force Mobile Field Hospital]] at Curico is already operational <ref>[http://www.mindef.gov.ar/info.asp?Id=1376 El hopital de Campa\u00f1a Argentino instalado en Chile ya est\u00e1 en functionamiento] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928113820/http://www.mindef.gov.ar/info.asp?Id=1376 |date=28 September 2011 }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Potash Corporation of Saskatchewan]] Inc. has donated $300,000.<ref>Global News, [http://news.globaltv.com/PotashCorp+makes+donation+Chile/2662894/story.html \"PotashCorp makes donation to Chile\"], Sarah Richter, 9 March 2010 (accessed 10 March 2010)</ref>\n\nWaste and recycling experts say that Constitucion's wreckage can be reused, and that proceeds from the sales of the rubble can help rebuilding efforts.<ref>AFP, [https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5ijZUgPemE4FgWV6YLWGbzZ6p2zUQ \"Recyclers see gold in Chile quake debris\"], Carlos Hamann, 9 March 2010 (accessed 10 March 2010)</ref>\n\n===9 March===\n[[Queensland, Australia]] has donated $500,000 to Chile.<ref>news.com.au, [http://www.news.com.au/breaking-news/state-donates-half-a-million-dollars-to-devastated-chile/story-e6frfku0-1225838940897 \"State donates half a million dollars to devastated Chile\"], AAP, 10 March 2010 (accessed 10 March 2010)</ref>\n\nA CMAT medical team was rerouted from Chile to Haiti after it was determined that there was a lesser need in Chile.<ref>Edmonton Sun, [http://www.edmontonsun.com/news/edmonton/2010/03/10/13186181.html \"Local ER docs rerouted from Chile to Haiti\"], Kristy Brownlee, 10 March 2010 (accessed 11 March 2010)</ref>\n\n===10 March===\nAn estimated $7 billion will be disbursed for insurance claims due to the earthquake.<ref>Sify, [http://sify.com/news/chile-earthquake-cost-insurers-up-to-7-bn-news-international-kdlkOfbbbej.html \"Chile earthquake cost insurers up to $7 bn\"], EFE, 11 March 201 (accessed 11 March 2010)</ref>\n\nThe US Congress has passed a bill to better allow for donations for Chilean quake relief.<ref>Focus, [http://www.focus-fen.net/index.php?id=n212738 \"US House approves Chile aid bill\"], AFP, 11 March 2010 (accessed 11 March 2010)</ref>\n\n===14 March===\nMore than 1600 people have been arrested for looting since the earthquake.<ref>Edmonton Journal, [https://edmontonjournal.com/news/Earthquake+looters+arrested/2681397/story.html \"Earthquake looters arrested\"], CanWest News Service, 14 March 2010 (accessed 14 March 2010)</ref>\n\n===16 March===\nAn estimate that 70,000 emergency shelters are needed was released.<ref>{{in lang|fr}} Figaro, [http://www.lefigaro.fr/flash-actu/2010/03/17/97001-20100317FILWWW00683-chili-70000-logements-necessaires.php \"Chili: 70.000 logements n\u00e9cessaires\"], AFP, 17 March 201. (accessed 20 March 2010)</ref>\n\n===19 March===\nThe Chilean government unveiled a $110 million recovery plan for the central regions.<ref>Channel News Asia, [http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/afp_world/view/1044806/1/.html \"Chile unveils US$110m reconstruction plan\"], AFP, 20 March 2010 (accessed 20 March 2010)</ref>\n\n===20 March===\nA geomapping cruise has been announced by the US NSF, to map the zone ruptured by the quake, and compare it to previous surveys of the seafloor of the zone.<ref>DNA India, [http://www.dnaindia.com/scitech/report_scientists-to-map-chile-earthquake-site-to-capture-fresh-data_1361326 \"Scientists to map Chile earthquake site to capture fresh data\"], ANI, 20 March 2010 (accessed 27 March 2010)</ref> The survey will use the ship ''Melville'', already on site, when the quake struck, and last eight days.<ref>UPI, [http://www.upi.com/Science_News/2010/03/23/Scientists-study-Chilean-earthquake/UPI-63121269375343/ \"Scientists study Chilean earthquake\"], 23 March 2010 (accessed 27 March 2010)</ref>\n\n===26 March===\nA charity tennis event, \"[[Champions for Chile]]\", has been announced for Saturday 3 April 2010. It would be held in [[Key Biscayne, Florida]], and be held in conjunction with the [[ATP Miami Masters]] of Sunday 4 April 2010. Among the players that would play are [[Andy Roddick]], [[Fernando Gonz\u00e1lez]], [[Gustavo Kuerten]] and [[Jim Courier]]. It is similar to the [[Hit for Haiti]] events for [[2010 Haiti earthquake]] relief. Proceeds would go to Hogar de Christo's Chilean earthquake relief.<ref>Times of India, [http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/tennis/top-stories/Roddick-signs-up-for-Chile-quake-relief-match/articleshow/5733176.cms \"Roddick signs up for Chile quake relief match\"], 'AFP', 27 March 2010 (accessed 30 March 2010)</ref><ref>CBC News, [http://stats.cbc.ca/tennis/story.asp?i=20100327180658230000101&ref=hea&tm=&src= \"Doubles for Chile relief planned at Key Biscayne\"], 27 March 2010 (accessed 30 March 2010)</ref>\n\n===5 April===\n400,000 students are to return to class in the affected region on 12 April.<ref>Latin American Herald Tribune, [http://www.laht.com/article.asp?ArticleId=354720&CategoryId=14094 \"400,000 Chilean Students Heading Back to School\"], 6 April 2010 (accessed 6 April 2010)</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[2010 Chile earthquake]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{2010 Chile earthquake}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Timeline Of Relief Efforts After The 2010 Chile Earthquake}}\n[[Category:2010 Chile earthquake]]\n", "name_user": "2001:8f8:1473:73a4:d4e2:4f5:40c3:fd78", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Hq)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Timeline_of_relief_efforts_after_the_2010_Chile_earthquake"}
{"title_page": "Bhadrajun", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = Bhadrajun\n| official_name                   = \n| other_name                      = \n| nickname                        = \n| settlement_type                 = Erstwhile Jagir [[Jodhpur State]], Town\n| image_skyline                   = In bhadrajun.jpg\n| image_alt                       = \n| image_caption                   = \n| pushpin_map                     = India Rajasthan#India\n| pushpin_label_position          = right\n| pushpin_map_alt                 = \n| pushpin_map_caption             = Location in Rajasthan, India\n| coordinates                     = {{coord|25.600|N|72.867|E|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type                = Country\n| subdivision_name                = {{flag|India}}\n| subdivision_type1               = [[States and territories of India|State]]\n| subdivision_name1               = [[Rajasthan]]\n| subdivision_type2               = [[List of districts of India|District]]\n| subdivision_name2               = [[Jalor district|Jalor]]\n| established_title               = <!-- Established -->\n| established_date                = \n| founder                         = Rao [[Jodha of Mandore]]\n| named_for                       = Subhdr-arjun\n| government_type                 = \n| governing_body                  = \n| unit_pref                       = Metric\n| area_footnotes                  = \n| area_rank                       = \n| area_total_km2                  = \n| elevation_footnotes             = \n| elevation_m                     = 225\n| population_total                = 5546\n| population_as_of                = 2011\n| population_rank                 = \n| population_density_km2          = auto\n| population_demonym              = \n| population_footnotes            = \n| demographics_type1              = Languages\n| demographics1_title1            = Official\n| demographics1_info1             = [[Hindi]]\n| timezone1                       = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1                     = +5:30\n| postal_code                     = 307029\n bhawani singh rathore            =8094752607     \n|area bhadrajun                   = 307029\n| registration_plate              = RJ-16\n| blank1_name_sec1                = [[Human sex ratio|Sex ratio]]\n| blank1_info_sec1                = 908 [[male|\u2642]]/[[female|\u2640]]\n| website                         = http://www.bhadrajunfort.com\n| footnotes                       = \n| demographic1_info2              = [[Marwari language|Marwari]],   [[Rajasthani language|Rajasthani]]\n| demographic1_title2             = Regional\n}}\n[[File:Bhadrajun blessing.jpg|right|thumb|260px|Blessing to the fort]]\n'''Bhadrajun''' is a village in the [[Jalore district]] of the western part of [[Rajasthan]], India, dating back to ancient times of the ''[[Mahabharata]]'' [[Indian epic poetry|epic]]. However, in recent centuries, it was the scene of warfare between the rulers of the [[Marwar|Marwar dynasty]] and of the [[Mughal Empire]].<ref name=jalore>{{Cite web|url= http://jalore.nic.in/tourism.html#historical|title= Historical Places|work= Qila\u2013Fort Bhadrajun|accessdate= 2009-11-15|publisher= National Informatics centre|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20090529091819/http://jalore.nic.in/tourism.html#historical|archive-date= 29 May 2009|url-status= dead|df= dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=arjun>{{Cite web |url= http://www.bhadrajunfort.com/ |title=Welcome to Bhadrajun Fort |accessdate=2009-11-15}}</ref>\n\nIn the 16th century, a fort known as the '''Bhadrajun Fort''' was built at Bhadrajun by the [[Rathore]] kings of [[Marwar]]. Today the fort is owned by Raja Shri Karanveer Singhji, the sixteenth descendant of Marwar Maharajas, who ruled from Jodhpur. It is now run as a heritage hotel. The fort has a significant collection of goods from its long past.<ref name=jalore/><ref name=arjun/>\n\n==Geography==\nBhadarjun is located in Jalore district within the [[Luni River]] basin.<ref name=district>{{Cite book |url= http://jalore.nic.in/geo.html |title= Geographic |accessdate= 2009-11-15 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20100221054639/http://jalore.nic.in/geo.html |archive-date= 21 February 2010 |url-status= dead }}</ref> It is situated in a [[tropical]] and [[semi-tropical]] climatic zone. The average annual and daily temperatures are high, with annual rainfall of {{convert|434|mm|in}}. January is the coldest month, with temperatures recorded between {{convert|1|and|2|C|F}}. Summer is very hot, recording an average daily temperature in the range of {{cvt|41|to|42|C|F}}. The highest temperature recorded was {{convert|48|C|F}} on a few days.<ref name=district/>\n\nAccording to the 2001 census, the population of Bhadrajun was 4,499, with 2,358 males and 2,141 females.<ref>{{Cite web |url= http://ourvillageindia.org/Place.aspx?PID=457628 |title=Bhadrajun Population |accessdate=2009-11-15}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Legend===\n[[File:Ravi Varma-Arjuna and Subhadra.jpg|left|thumb|200px|Arjuna and Subhadra were married in Bhadrajun]]\nThe word \u2018Bhadrajun\u2019 is directly linked to the ''[[Mahabharata]]'' [[Indian epic poetry|epic]]. Bhadrajun is made up of two words, the name of '[[Subhadra]]', sister of [[Lord Krishna]], plus '[[Arjuna]]', the third among the five [[Pandava]] brothers of Mahabharata. Initially, it was called \"Subhdr-arjun\" but over the years it was changed to the colloquial usage of the single word \"Bhadrajun\". The legend linked to this name is a story of romance.<ref name=jalore/>\n\nAccording to the ''Mahabharata'' legend, Lord Krishna advised Arjuna to marry sister from [[Dwarka]] (where she resided with her parents). The reason for Krishna's advice was because Arjuna, along with his four brothers, was under a [[vanvas]] (incognito living), as per the demand  of the Kauravas, for having lost their kingdom in a dice game. However, Arjuna, who was disguised as a saint, fell in love with the daughter of [[Vasudeva]] (maternal uncle of Arjuna), Subhadra. Arjuna spent the last year of his 13-year exile period in Dwarka. Krishna, who was aware of this fact, advised Arjuna to escape with his sister so that his true identity would not be revealed during the marriage. Identification would have resulted in a further 13 years in exile as per Pandava's pact with the Kauravas. It would have also invited the wrath of [[Balarama]], brother of Krishna who wanted the Kaurava king [[Duryodhana]] to marry Subhadra. Lord Krishna was not in favour of such an alliance as he was particularly attached to Arjuna, and wished nothing but the best for his sister Subhadra.<ref name=jalore/><ref name=fort>{{Cite web |url= http://www.bhadrajunfort.com/about_fort.htm|title=About Fort |work=The History |accessdate=2009-11-15 |publisher= Bhadrajunfort.com}}</ref><ref name=story>{{Cite web |url= http://www.harekrsna.com/sun/features/03-08/features951.htm |title= The Marriage of Arjun and Subhadra |accessdate=2009-11-15 |publisher= Hare Krishna.com}}</ref><ref name=Bhadra>{{Cite web |url=http://www.fairytaleindia.com/package-book.php?pkgId=154&categId=20#POS6 |title=Marwar horse Safari |work=Bhadrajun |accessdate=2009-11-21 |quote=\u2026towards the historic castle of Bhadrajun. It is here that Pandav prince Arjun married Lord Krishna's sister Suhhadra thus getting its name Bhadrajun. The majestic palace of Bhadrajun dates back to l6th century and is a running heritage hotel |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091111164547/http://www.fairytaleindia.com/package-book.php?pkgId=154&categId=20#POS6 |archive-date=11 November 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=Dange>{{Cite book |last=Dange |first= Sadashiv Ambadas |title= Encyclopaedia of puranic beliefs and practices, Volume 4 |work=Legend of Subhadra |page=1398 |accessdate=2009-11-21 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=H23XAAAAMAAJ&q=Legend+of+Subhadra&dq=Legend+of+Subhadra |publisher= Navrang |year=1990 |isbn= 978-81-7013-056-7}}</ref>\n\nArjuna, in disguise of a saint, fled from Dwarka with Subhadra in a chariot, in full view of Krishna and Vasudeva and the family members. After an arduous journey of three days and two nights, through mostly uninhabited forest area, they reached the valley near Bhadrajun where they decided to get married, before proceeding to [[Indraprastha]], their capital. The marriage was conducted by a local [[Brahmin]] priest. The Brahmin priest was given an [[earring]] (''vali'' in local language) by Subhadra and a [[conch-shell]] by Arjuna as fee for performing their marriage. The village of the Brahmin was named thereafter as \u2018sankhavali\u2019 (in the word \"sankavali\", \u2018sankh\u2019 means \u2018conch-shell\u2019 and \u2018vali\u2019 means \"ear ring\"). It is also said that Balarama, though furious initially with Arjuna did not chase him to stop the marriage. He was persuaded by Krishna and Vasudeva to forgive Arjuna and Subhadra, given that they were in love with each other. Convinced of this fact, Balarama later sent gifts to his sister - a [[dowry]] of jewellery, elephants, chariots, horses, servants and maidservants. Following this marriage, Bhadarjun grew in population. A small temple in the name of Subhadra, popularly known as the \"Dhumda Mata\", exists even now in a nearby village.<ref name=jalore/><ref name=fort/><ref name=story/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.flyandbike.be/Rajasthan%20individueel%202009.pdf|format=pdf|title=India Rajasthan|work=Day 8 Cycle to Bhadrajun|accessdate=2009-11-21|quote=According to the Mahabharata, the Pandava prince Arjun eloped with Subhadra, the sister of Lord Krishna and married in this valley.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706134056/http://www.flyandbike.be/Rajasthan%20individueel%202009.pdf|archive-date=6 July 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Early history===\nWhile the mythological history of Bhadrajun is traced to Arjuna who lived in the [[treta yuga]], one of the four [[Hindu]] [[eras]] of ''Mahabharata''; the history of Bhadrajun and the Marwar rulers of Jodhpur can only be traced from the 16th century. Several historic wars took place in Bhadrajun, initially against the [[Suri dynasty]] and later against the [[Mughal dynasty]] rulers.<ref name=jalore/><ref name=fort/>\n\nThe earliest ruler who occupied Bhadrajun was Thakur Rattan Singh, fifth son of Rao Maldeo, the [[Maharaja of Jodhpur]] in 1549. It was a [[feudatory|feudal land]] under the Jodhpur kingdom, which had ten land lords who were called ''Rajas'' or ''Thikanas'', out of a total of 1,891 land lords.  These ten Rajas were known as ''Sirayats'' in the State of \"Jodhpur Marwar\". They held high positions in the court of Jodhpur. The Bhadrajun feudatory was also one of the ten feudatories which received special privileges in the court.<ref name=jalore/><ref name=fort/> In the seating arrangement in the Jodhpur court, the Raja of Bhadrajun was always seated to the right of the king, since he belonged to the king's lineage. Sixteen generations of Marwars ruled from Bhadrajun.<ref name=jalore/><ref name=fort/>\n\n===Lineage and wars===\nThe first to rule from Bhadrajun was Raja Ratan Singh, son of  [[Maharaja of Jodhpur|Rao Maldeo]] (also known as Chandra Sen).\n\nMaldeo of Jodhpur (also known as Maldeo Rathore), father of Ratan Singh, soon after becoming King of [[Marwar]], launched war campaigns and successfully defeated the Sindhals and annexed Bhadrajun.<ref name=Ratnawat>{{Cite book|last=Ratnawat|first= Shyam Singh|author2=Krishna Gopal Sharma|title= History and culture of Rajasthan: from earliest times up to 1956 A.D|work=Bhadrajun|page=163|accessdate=2009-11-15|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6yNuAAAAMAAJ&q=Bhadrajun&dq=| publisher= Centre for Rajasthan Studies, University of Rajasthan|year=1999}}</ref>\n\nIn 1543, Ratan Singh fought at [[Girari]] (Sumel) against the invading army of [[Sher Shah Suri]] (the first ruler of Suri Dynasty), the then Emperor of India. He also fought a second battle at [[Merata]], when he suffered injuries and was subsequently defeated by Viram Deo.<ref name=fort/>\n\nIn 1563\u201364, the Rathores lost their capital city of Jhodpur to [[Pathan Malik]], a commander of the [[Mughal Emperor]] [[Akbar]], but they retained their territory around Bhadrajun.<ref name=fort/><ref>Ratnawat p.177</ref> During this war, they could not sustain their army's needs as adequate provisions were not available inside the fort. Also, there was no help forthcoming from outside powers. Maldeo, also known as Rana Chandrasen, abandoned the fort and  reached Bhadarajun and remained there for seven years.<ref name=Sinh>{{Cite book |last=Sinh |first=Raghubir |title= Durga Das Rathor |work=Bhdarjun |page=11 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=y4QKAQAAIAAJ&q=Bhadrajun&dq=Bhadrajun |publisher= National Book Trust, India: distributors, Thomson Press (India) |year=1975}}</ref><ref name=Bhargava>{{Cite book |last=Bhargava |title= Marwar and the Mughal emperors (A. D. 1526-1748) |work=Bhdrajun |page=46 |accessdate=2009-11-15 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=dbY9AAAAIAAJ&q=Bhadrajun&dq=Bhadrajun&lr=|publisher= Munshiram Manoharlal |year=1966}}</ref>\n\nIn 1651, Mukan Dasji of Bhadrajun fought against Raja Sawai Sur Singhji of Jodhpur in the battle against the Mughals at Mandavgarh. His bravery was duly rewarded with recognition of Bhadarajun as his ''[[jagir]]'' (estate) with a due ''[[patta (document)|patta]]'' (document).<ref name=fort/>\n\nWhen Emperor [[Aurangzeb]]'s army attacked Jodhpur, Udai Bhanji of Bhadrajun fought for Maharaja Jaswant Singh and saved the Maharaja's life. As a reward, he married the niece of the Maharana. Subsequently, he went to [[Peshawar]] to fight war against the [[Afghanistan|Pathan]]\u2019s. But in 1785, in the battle against the Mughal Emperor of India, he was killed. His wife, Jas Kanwar of Dodiali, committed [[Sati (practice)|Sati]] ('sati' was an act of self-immolation undertaken by the wife on the pyre of her husband, a practice prevalent then in many parts of India).<ref name=fort/>\n\nSubsequent rulers of Bhadrajun were also involved in several battles with the kingdom of Jodhpur and with other feudatories in the region. Finally, Bhadrajun merged with the [[Dominion of India|Union of India]], after India became independent in August 1947. The last [[kinship|scion]] of the dynasty, Raja Gopal Singh, now owns the estate and manages it as a heritage hotel.<ref name=fort/>\n\n==Monuments==\n[[File:Ganesh blessing.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Ganesha on the wall of the fort]]\nThere are a number of historic monuments in and around the village Bhadrajun. The best known is the Bhadrajun fort due to its history and status as a heritage hotel.\n\n===Bhadrajun fort===\nThe fort is constructed on top of the hill and although small, it was built as a strong hill fort. It is also strategically located in the village of Bhadrajun, which is also securely protected since it is enclosed in a horse shoe shape valley with one entry from the east. The fort walls are {{convert|20|-|30|ft|m}} high, built at strategical locations around the village with a uniform width of {{convert|10|ft|m}}. Bastions, known as [[burjis]], were built to erect canons and to eject arrows against invaders. The average elevation of the place is {{convert|2000|ft|m}} above m.s.l.<ref name=fort/>\n\nThe fort is built on rugged hills with forest vegetation consisting of trees, [[cacti]], [[bushes]] and rocks. The forest around the fort is inhabited by wildlife such as [[jackal]]s, [[wild cat]]s, [[blue bull]]s, [[hedge hog]]s and [[fox]]es. The fort has been converted into a luxury hotel, with 14 furnished rooms, all with a [[Bathroom|bathroom ensuite]].<ref name=fort/><ref name=heritage>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wtmlondon.com/ExhibitorLibrary/6907/horse_safari_7.pdf|format=pdf|title=Horse Safari in Rajasthan|work=Bhenswara \u2013 Bhadrajun. Riding Distance 34km|accessdate=2009-11-15}}{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Visitor information==\nBhadrajun is {{convert|97|km|mi}} from Jodhpur. Jodhpur is well connected by road, rail and air links with rest of the country.<ref name=fort/>\n\nBy road, Bhadrajun is {{convert|54|km|mi}} away from [[Jalore]], the district headquarters, on the Jalore-Jodhpur road, {{convert|200|km|mi}} from [[Udaipur]], {{convert|356|km|mi}} from [[Jaipur]] and {{convert|618|km|mi}} from [[Delhi]].\n\n[[Pali, Rajasthan|Pali]] is the nearest railway station on the [[broad gauge]] line. The nearest airport is at Jodhpur, {{convert|97|km|mi}}  away.<ref name=insight>{{Cite web|url=http://www.insights2india.com/royal_rajwada_bhadrajun.html|title=Royal Rajwada, Bhadrajun|accessdate=2009-11-15|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100720032820/http://www.insights2india.com/royal_rajwada_bhadrajun.html|archivedate=2010-07-20}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Bhadrajun}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Jalore district]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Jalore district]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = Bhadrajun\n| official_name                   = \n| other_name                      = \n| nickname                        = \n| settlement_type                 = Erstwhile Jagir [[Jodhpur State]], Town\n| image_skyline                   = In bhadrajun.jpg\n| image_alt                       = \n| image_caption                   = \n| pushpin_map                     = India Rajasthan#India\n| pushpin_label_position          = right\n| pushpin_map_alt                 = \n| pushpin_map_caption             = Location in Rajasthan, India\n| coordinates                     = {{coord|25.600|N|72.867|E|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type                = Country\n| subdivision_name                = {{flag|India}}\n| subdivision_type1               = [[States and territories of India|State]]\n| subdivision_name1               = [[Rajasthan]]\n| subdivision_type2               = [[List of districts of India|District]]\n| subdivision_name2               = [[Jalor district|Jalor]]\n| established_title               = <!-- Established -->\n| established_date                = \n| founder                         = Rao [[Jodha of Mandore]]\n| named_for                       = Subhdr-arjun\n| government_type                 = \n| governing_body                  = \n| unit_pref                       = Metric\n| area_footnotes                  = \n| area_rank                       = \n| area_total_km2                  = \n| elevation_footnotes             = \n| elevation_m                     = 225\n| population_total                = 5546\n| population_as_of                = 2011\n| population_rank                 = \n| population_density_km2          = auto\n| population_demonym              = \n| population_footnotes            = \n| demographics_type1              = Languages\n| demographics1_title1            = Official\n| demographics1_info1             = [[Hindi]]\n| timezone1                       = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1                     = +5:30\n| postal_code                     = 307029\n bhawani singh rathore            =8094752607     \n|area bhadrajun                   = 307029\n| registration_plate              = RJ-16\n| blank1_name_sec1                = [[Human sex ratio|Sex ratio]]\n| blank1_info_sec1                = 908 [[male|\u2642]]/[[female|\u2640]]\n| website                         = http://www.bhadrajunfort.com\n| footnotes                       = \n| demographic1_info2              = [[Marwari language|Marwari]],   [[Rajasthani language|Rajasthani]]\n| demographic1_title2             = Regional\n}}\n[[File:Bhadrajun blessing.jpg|right|thumb|260px|Blessing to the fort]]\n'''Bhadrajun''' is a village in the [[Jalore district]] of the western part of [[Rajasthan]], India, dating back to ancient times of the ''[[Mahabharata]]'' [[Indian epic poetry|epic]]. However, in recent centuries, it was the scene of warfare between the rulers of the [[Marwar|Marwar dynasty]] and of the [[Mughal Empire]].<ref name=jalore>{{Cite web|url= http://jalore.nic.in/tourism.html#historical|title= Historical Places|work= Qila\u2013Fort Bhadrajun|accessdate= 2009-11-15|publisher= National Informatics centre|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20090529091819/http://jalore.nic.in/tourism.html#historical|archive-date= 29 May 2009|url-status= dead|df= dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=arjun>{{Cite web |url= http://www.bhadrajunfort.com/ |title=Welcome to Bhadrajun Fort |accessdate=2009-11-15}}</ref>\n\nIn the 16th century, a fort known as the '''Bhadrajun Fort''' was built at Bhadrajun by the [[Rathore]] kings of [[Marwar]]. Today the fort is owned by Raja Shri Karanveer Singhji, the sixteenth descendant of Marwar Maharajas, who ruled from Jodhpur. It is now run as a heritage hotel. The fort has a significant collection of goods from its long past.<ref name=jalore/><ref name=arjun/>\n\n==Geography==\nBhadarjun is located in Jalore district within the [[Luni River]] basin.<ref name=district>{{Cite book |url= http://jalore.nic.in/geo.html |title= Geographic |accessdate= 2009-11-15 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20100221054639/http://jalore.nic.in/geo.html |archive-date= 21 February 2010 |url-status= dead }}</ref> It is situated in a [[tropical]] and [[semi-tropical]] climatic zone. The average annual and daily temperatures are high, with annual rainfall of {{convert|434|mm|in}}. January is the coldest month, with temperatures recorded between {{convert|1|and|2|C|F}}. Summer is very hot, recording an average daily temperature in the range of {{cvt|41|to|42|C|F}}. The highest temperature recorded was {{convert|48|C|F}} on a few days.<ref name=district/>\n\nAccording to the 2001 census, the population of Bhadrajun was 4,499, with 2,358 males and 2,141 females.<ref>{{Cite web |url= http://ourvillageindia.org/Place.aspx?PID=457628 |title=Bhadrajun Population |accessdate=2009-11-15}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Legend===\n[[File:Ravi Varma-Arjuna and Subhadra.jpg|left|thumb|200px|Arjuna and Subhadra were married in Bhadrajun]]\nThe word \u2018Bhadrajun\u2019 is directly linked to the ''[[Mahabharata]]'' [[Indian epic poetry|epic]]. Bhadrajun is made up of two words, the name of '[[Subhadra]]', sister of [[Lord Krishna]], plus '[[Arjuna]]', the third among the five [[Pandava]] brothers of Mahabharata. Initially, it was called \"Subhdr-arjun\" but over the years it was changed to the colloquial usage of the single word \"Bhadrajun\". The legend linked to this name is a story of romance.<ref name=jalore/>\n\nAccording to the ''Mahabharata'' legend, Lord Krishna advised Arjuna to marry sister from [[Dwarka]] (where she resided with her parents). The reason for Krishna's advice was because Arjuna, along with his four brothers, was under a [[vanvas]] (incognito living), as per the demand  of the Kauravas, for having lost their kingdom in a dice game. However, Arjuna, who was disguised as a saint, fell in love with the daughter of [[Vasudeva]] (maternal uncle of Arjuna), Subhadra. Arjuna spent the last year of his 13-year exile period in Dwarka. Krishna, who was aware of this fact, advised Arjuna to escape with his sister so that his true identity would not be revealed during the marriage. Identification would have resulted in a further 13 years in exile as per Pandava's pact with the Kauravas. It would have also invited the wrath of [[Balarama]], brother of Krishna who wanted the Kaurava king [[Duryodhana]] to marry Subhadra. Lord Krishna was not in favour of such an alliance as he was particularly attached to Arjuna, and wished nothing but the best for his sister Subhadra.<ref name=jalore/><ref name=fort>{{Cite web |url= http://www.bhadrajunfort.com/about_fort.htm|title=About Fort |work=The History |accessdate=2009-11-15 |publisher= Bhadrajunfort.com}}</ref><ref name=story>{{Cite web |url= http://www.harekrsna.com/sun/features/03-08/features951.htm |title= The Marriage of Arjun and Subhadra |accessdate=2009-11-15 |publisher= Hare Krishna.com}}</ref><ref name=Bhadra>{{Cite web |url=http://www.fairytaleindia.com/package-book.php?pkgId=154&categId=20#POS6 |title=Marwar horse Safari |work=Bhadrajun |accessdate=2009-11-21 |quote=\u2026towards the historic castle of Bhadrajun. It is here that Pandav prince Arjun married Lord Krishna's sister Suhhadra thus getting its name Bhadrajun. The majestic palace of Bhadrajun dates back to l6th century and is a running heritage hotel |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091111164547/http://www.fairytaleindia.com/package-book.php?pkgId=154&categId=20#POS6 |archive-date=11 November 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=Dange>{{Cite book |last=Dange |first= Sadashiv Ambadas |title= Encyclopaedia of puranic beliefs and practices, Volume 4 |work=Legend of Subhadra |page=1398 |accessdate=2009-11-21 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=H23XAAAAMAAJ&q=Legend+of+Subhadra&dq=Legend+of+Subhadra |publisher= Navrang |year=1990 |isbn= 978-81-7013-056-7}}</ref>\n\nArjuna, in disguise of a saint, fled from Dwarka with Subhadra in a chariot, in full view of Krishna and Vasudeva and the family members. After an arduous journey of three days and two nights, through mostly uninhabited forest area, they reached the valley near Bhadrajun where they decided to get married, before proceeding to [[Indraprastha]], their capital. The marriage was conducted by a local [[Brahmin]] priest. The Brahmin priest was given an [[earring]] (''vali'' in local language) by Subhadra and a [[conch-shell]] by Arjuna as fee for performing their marriage. The village of the Brahmin was named thereafter as \u2018sankhavali\u2019 (in the word \"sankavali\", \u2018sankh\u2019 means \u2018conch-shell\u2019 and \u2018vali\u2019 means \"ear ring\"). It is also said that Balarama, though furious initially with Arjuna did not chase him to stop the marriage. He was persuaded by Krishna and Vasudeva to forgive Arjuna and Subhadra, given that they were in love with each other. Convinced of this fact, Balarama later sent gifts to his sister - a [[dowry]] of jewellery, elephants, chariots, horses, servants and maidservants. Following this marriage, Bhadarjun grew in population. A small temple in the name of Subhadra, popularly known as the \"Dhumda Mata\", exists even now in a nearby village.<ref name=jalore/><ref name=fort/><ref name=story/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.flyandbike.be/Rajasthan%20individueel%202009.pdf|format=pdf|title=India Rajasthan|work=Day 8 Cycle to Bhadrajun|accessdate=2009-11-21|quote=According to the Mahabharata, the Pandava prince Arjun eloped with Subhadra, the sister of Lord Krishna and married in this valley.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706134056/http://www.flyandbike.be/Rajasthan%20individueel%202009.pdf|archive-date=6 July 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Early history===\nWhile the mythological history of Bhadrajun is traced to Arjuna who lived in the [[treta yuga]], one of the four [[Hindu]] [[eras]] of ''Mahabharata''; the history of Bhadrajun and the Marwar rulers of Jodhpur can only be traced from the 16th century. Several historic wars took place in Bhadrajun, initially against the [[Suri dynasty]] and later against the [[Mughal dynasty]] rulers.<ref name=jalore/><ref name=fort/>\n\nThe earliest ruler who occupied Bhadrajun was Thakur Rattan Singh, fifth son of Rao Maldeo, the [[Maharaja of Jodhpur]] in 1549. It was a [[feudatory|feudal land]] under the Jodhpur kingdom, which had ten land lords who were called ''Rajas'' or ''Thikanas'', out of a total of 1,891 land lords.  These ten Rajas were known as ''Sirayats'' in the State of \"Jodhpur Marwar\". They held high positions in the court of Jodhpur. The Bhadrajun feudatory was also one of the ten feudatories which received special privileges in the court.<ref name=jalore/><ref name=fort/> In the seating arrangement in the Jodhpur court, the Raja of Bhadrajun was always seated to the right of the king, since he belonged to the king's lineage. Sixteen generations of Marwars ruled from Bhadrajun.<ref name=jalore/><ref name=fort/>\n\n===Lineage and wars===\nThe first to rule from Bhadrajun was Raja Ratan Singh, son of  [[Maharaja of Jodhpur|Rao Maldeo]] (also known as Chandra Sen).\n\nMaldeo of Jodhpur (also known as Maldeo Rathore), father of Ratan Singh, soon after becoming King of [[Marwar]], launched war campaigns and successfully defeated the Sindhals and annexed Bhadrajun.<ref name=Ratnawat>{{Cite book|last=Ratnawat|first= Shyam Singh|author2=Krishna Gopal Sharma|title= History and culture of Rajasthan: from earliest times up to 1956 A.D|work=Bhadrajun|page=163|accessdate=2009-11-15|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6yNuAAAAMAAJ&q=Bhadrajun&dq=| publisher= Centre for Rajasthan Studies, University of Rajasthan|year=1999}}</ref>\n\nIn 1543, Ratan Singh fought at [[Girari]] (Sumel) against the invading army of [[Sher Shah Suri]] (the first ruler of Suri Dynasty), the then Emperor of India. He also fought a second battle at [[Merata]], when he suffered injuries and was subsequently defeated by Viram Deo.<ref name=fort/>\n\nIn 1563\u201364, the Rathores lost their capital city of Jhodpur to [[Pathan Malik]], a commander of the [[Mughal Emperor]] [[Akbar]], but they retained their territory around Bhadrajun.<ref name=fort/><ref>Ratnawat p.177</ref> During this war, they could not sustain their army's needs as adequate provisions were not available inside the fort. Also, there was no help forthcoming from outside powers. Maldeo, also known as Rana Chandrasen, abandoned the fort and  reached Bhadarajun and remained there for seven years.<ref name=Sinh>{{Cite book |last=Sinh |first=Raghubir |title= Durga Das Rathor |work=Bhdarjun |page=11 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=y4QKAQAAIAAJ&q=Bhadrajun&dq=Bhadrajun |publisher= National Book Trust, India: distributors, Thomson Press (India) |year=1975}}</ref><ref name=Bhargava>{{Cite book |last=Bhargava |title= Marwar and the Mughal emperors (A. D. 1526-1748) |work=Bhdrajun |page=46 |accessdate=2009-11-15 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=dbY9AAAAIAAJ&q=Bhadrajun&dq=Bhadrajun&lr=|publisher= Munshiram Manoharlal |year=1966}}</ref>\n\nIn 1651, Mukan Dasji of Bhadrajun fought against Raja Sawai Sur Singhji of Jodhpur in the battle against the Mughals at Mandavgarh. His bravery was duly rewarded with recognition of Bhadarajun as his ''[[jagir]]'' (estate) with a due ''[[patta (document)|patta]]'' (document).<ref name=fort/>\n\nWhen Emperor [[Aurangzeb]]'s army attacked Jodhpur, Udai Bhanji of Bhadrajun fought for Maharaja Jaswant Singh and saved the Maharaja's life. As a reward, he married the niece of the Maharana. Subsequently, he went to [[Peshawar]] to fight war against the [[Afghanistan|Pathan]]\u2019s. But in 1785, in the battle against the Mughal Emperor of India, he was killed. His wife, Jas Kanwar of Dodiali, committed [[Sati (practice)|Sati]] ('sati' was an act of self-immolation undertaken by the wife on the pyre of her husband, a practice prevalent then in many parts of India).<ref name=fort/>\n\nSubsequent rulers of Bhadrajun were also involved in several battles with the kingdom of Jodhpur and with other feudatories in the region. Finally, Bhadrajun merged with the [[Union of India]], after India became independent in August 1947. The last [[kinship|scion]] of the dynasty, Raja Gopal Singh, now owns the estate and manages it as a heritage hotel.<ref name=fort/>\n\n==Monuments==\n[[File:Ganesh blessing.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Ganesha on the wall of the fort]]\nThere are a number of historic monuments in and around the village Bhadrajun. The best known is the Bhadrajun fort due to its history and status as a heritage hotel.\n\n===Bhadrajun fort===\nThe fort is constructed on top of the hill and although small, it was built as a strong hill fort. It is also strategically located in the village of Bhadrajun, which is also securely protected since it is enclosed in a horse shoe shape valley with one entry from the east. The fort walls are {{convert|20|-|30|ft|m}} high, built at strategical locations around the village with a uniform width of {{convert|10|ft|m}}. Bastions, known as [[burjis]], were built to erect canons and to eject arrows against invaders. The average elevation of the place is {{convert|2000|ft|m}} above m.s.l.<ref name=fort/>\n\nThe fort is built on rugged hills with forest vegetation consisting of trees, [[cacti]], [[bushes]] and rocks. The forest around the fort is inhabited by wildlife such as [[jackal]]s, [[wild cat]]s, [[blue bull]]s, [[hedge hog]]s and [[fox]]es. The fort has been converted into a luxury hotel, with 14 furnished rooms, all with a [[Bathroom|bathroom ensuite]].<ref name=fort/><ref name=heritage>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wtmlondon.com/ExhibitorLibrary/6907/horse_safari_7.pdf|format=pdf|title=Horse Safari in Rajasthan|work=Bhenswara \u2013 Bhadrajun. Riding Distance 34km|accessdate=2009-11-15}}{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Visitor information==\nBhadrajun is {{convert|97|km|mi}} from Jodhpur. Jodhpur is well connected by road, rail and air links with rest of the country.<ref name=fort/>\n\nBy road, Bhadrajun is {{convert|54|km|mi}} away from [[Jalore]], the district headquarters, on the Jalore-Jodhpur road, {{convert|200|km|mi}} from [[Udaipur]], {{convert|356|km|mi}} from [[Jaipur]] and {{convert|618|km|mi}} from [[Delhi]].\n\n[[Pali, Rajasthan|Pali]] is the nearest railway station on the [[broad gauge]] line. The nearest airport is at Jodhpur, {{convert|97|km|mi}}  away.<ref name=insight>{{Cite web|url=http://www.insights2india.com/royal_rajwada_bhadrajun.html|title=Royal Rajwada, Bhadrajun|accessdate=2009-11-15|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100720032820/http://www.insights2india.com/royal_rajwada_bhadrajun.html|archivedate=2010-07-20}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Bhadrajun}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Jalore district]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Jalore district]]\n", "name_user": "DrKay", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bhadrajun"}
{"title_page": "Russell County, Kentucky", "text_new": "{{Distinguish|Russell, Kentucky}}\n{{Infobox U.S. county\n| county = Russell County\n| state = Kentucky\n| seal =\n| founded year = December 14, 1825\n| founded date =\n| seat wl = Jamestown\n| largest city wl = Russell Springs\n| area_total_sq_mi = 283\n| area_land_sq_mi = 254\n| area_water_sq_mi = 29\n| area percentage = 10\n| population_as_of = 2010\n| population_total = 17565\n| pop_est_as_of = 2018\n| population_est = 17821\n| population_density_sq_mi = auto\n| time zone = Central\n| footnotes =\n| web = www.russellcountyky.com\n| named for = [[William Russell (Kentucky)|William Russell]]\n| ex image = Russell County Courthouse, Jamestown.jpg\n| ex image cap = Russell County courthouse in Jamestown\n| district =1st\n}}\n\n'''Russell County''' is a [[County (United States)|county]] located in the [[Commonwealth (U.S. state)|U.S. Commonwealth]] of [[Kentucky]]. As of the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]], the population was 17,565.<ref name=\"QF\">{{cite web|title=State & County QuickFacts|url=http://quickfacts.census.gov/qfd/states/21/21207.html|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=March 6, 2014}}</ref> Its [[county seat]] is [[Jamestown, Kentucky|Jamestown]].<ref name=\"GR6\">{{cite web|url=http://www.naco.org/Counties/Pages/FindACounty.aspx|accessdate=2011-06-07|title=Find a County|publisher=National Association of Counties}}</ref> The county was formed on December 14, 1825, from portions of [[Adair County, Kentucky|Adair]], [[Cumberland County, Kentucky|Cumberland]] and [[Wayne County, Kentucky|Wayne]] Counties and is named for [[William Russell (Kentucky)|William Russell]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kyenc.org/entry/r/RUSSE03.html|title=Russell County|publisher=The Kentucky Encyclopedia|year=2000|accessdate=August 23, 2014}}</ref> It has been a prohibition or [[dry county]], meaning that the sale of [[alcoholic beverages|alcohol]] was prohibited, but in a referendum on Jan. 19, 2016, the county voted 3,833 to 3,423 to go \"wet.\"<ref>{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=luoxAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA36#v=onepage&q&f=false | title=The Register of the Kentucky State Historical Society, Volume 1 | publisher=Kentucky State Historical Society | year=1903 | pages=36}}</ref><ref>http://www.russellcountynewspapers.com/editionviewer/?Edition=b7e46efc-0b0d-401a-84c6-1badcd7e9a8d</ref>\n\nIn 2015, the cities of Jamestown and Russell Springs became two of the first [[gigabit]] Internet communities in Kentucky with the completion of a state-of-the-art [[optical fiber]] network by the local telephone cooperative.<ref>https://duocounty.com/news-information/25-jamestown-russell-springs-columbia-among-first-in-kentucky-to-be-gigabit-internet-communities</ref>\n\n[[Wolf Creek Dam]] is located in southern Russell County. The dam impounds [[Cumberland River]] to form [[Lake Cumberland]], a major tourism attraction for the county. [[Wolf Creek National Fish Hatchery]] is also located in Russell County just below the dam.\n\n==Geography==\nAccording to the [[U.S. Census Bureau]], the county has a total area of {{convert|283|sqmi}}, of which {{convert|254|sqmi}} is land and {{convert|29|sqmi}} (10%) is water.<ref name=\"GR1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/geo/maps-data/data/docs/gazetteer/counties_list_21.txt|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=August 19, 2014|date=August 22, 2012|title=2010 Census Gazetteer Files|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140812210847/http://www.census.gov/geo/maps-data/data/docs/gazetteer/counties_list_21.txt|archivedate=August 12, 2014}}</ref> The highest point is {{convert|1140|ft|m}} atop Dickerson Ridge in the extreme northern part of the county and the lowest point is {{convert|530|ft|m}} along the [[Cumberland River]].\n\n===Major highways===\n* [[Cumberland Parkway]]\n* [[U.S. Route 127 in Kentucky]]\n* [[Kentucky Route 80]]\n\n===Adjacent counties===\n* [[Casey County, Kentucky|Casey County]]  (north/EST Border)\n* [[Pulaski County, Kentucky|Pulaski County]]  (northeast/EST Border)\n* [[Wayne County, Kentucky|Wayne County]]  (southeast/EST Border)\n* [[Clinton County, Kentucky|Clinton County]]  (south)\n* [[Cumberland County, Kentucky|Cumberland County]]  (southwest)\n* [[Adair County, Kentucky|Adair County]]  (west)\n\n==Demographics==\n\n{{US Census population\n|1830= 3879\n|1840= 4238\n|1850= 5349\n|1860= 6024\n|1870= 5809\n|1880= 7591\n|1890= 8136\n|1900= 9695\n|1910= 10861\n|1920= 11854\n|1930= 11930\n|1940= 13615\n|1950= 13717\n|1960= 11076\n|1970= 10542\n|1980= 13708\n|1990= 14716\n|2000= 16315\n|2010= 17565\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=17821\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=July 29, 2019}}</ref>\n|align-fn=center\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/decennial-census.html|title=U.S. Decennial Census|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=August 19, 2014}}</ref><br />1790\u20131960<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mapserver.lib.virginia.edu|title=Historical Census Browser|publisher=University of Virginia Library|accessdate=August 19, 2014}}</ref> 1900\u20131990<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/population/cencounts/ky190090.txt|title=Population of Counties by Decennial Census: 1900 to 1990|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=August 19, 2014}}</ref><br />1990\u20132000<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/population/www/cen2000/briefs/phc-t4/tables/tab02.pdf|title=Census 2000 PHC-T-4. Ranking Tables for Counties: 1990 and 2000|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=August 19, 2014}}</ref> 2010\u20132013<ref name=\"QF\"/>\n}}\n\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2008-01-31|title=U.S. Census website}}</ref> of 2000, there were 16,315 people, 6,941 households, and 4,796 families residing in the county.  The [[population density]] was {{convert|64|/sqmi|/km2}}.  There were 9,064 housing units at an average density of {{convert|36|/sqmi|/km2}}.  The racial makeup of the county was 98.34% [[Race (United States Census)|White]], 0.58% [[Race (United States Census)|Black]] or [[Race (United States Census)|African American]], 0.12% [[Race (United States Census)|Native American]], 0.14% [[Race (United States Census)|Asian]], 0.02% [[Race (United States Census)|Pacific Islander]], 0.21% from [[Race (United States Census)|other races]], and 0.59% from two or more races.  0.86% of the population were [[Race (United States Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Race (United States Census)|Latino]] of any race.\n\nThere were 6,941 households out of which 29.00% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 55.30% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 10.20% had a female householder with no husband present, and 30.90% were non-families. 28.00% of all households were made up of individuals and 12.90% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.  The average household size was 2.33 and the average family size was 2.82.\n\nIn the county, the population was spread out with 22.50% under the age of 18, 7.50% from 18 to 24, 27.50% from 25 to 44, 25.90% from 45 to 64, and 16.50% who were 65 years of age or older.  The median age was 40 years. For every 100 females there were 93.90 males.  For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 91.00 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the county was $22,042, and the median income for a family was $27,803. Males had a median income of $24,193 versus $18,289 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the county was $13,183.  About 20.40% of families and 24.30% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 30.80% of those under age 18 and 27.30% of those age 65 or over.\n\n==Politics==\nRussell County is part of the historically and currently rock-ribbed Republican bloc of southeastern Kentucky that also includes such counties as [[Clinton County, Kentucky|Clinton]], [[Cumberland County, Kentucky|Cumberland]], [[Casey County, Kentucky|Casey]], [[Pulaski County, Kentucky|Pulaski]], [[Laurel County, Kentucky|Laurel]], [[Rockcastle County, Kentucky|Rockcastle]], [[Monroe County, Kentucky|Monroe]], [[McCreary County, Kentucky|McCreary]], [[Clay County, Kentucky|Clay]], [[Jackson County, Kentucky|Jackson]], [[Owsley County, Kentucky|Owsley]] and [[Leslie County, Kentucky|Leslie]]. These counties were opposed to secession during [[Kentucky in the American Civil War|the Civil War era]], and consequently became and have remained intensely Republican ever since.<ref name=\"How\">Sullivan, Robert David; [http://www.americamagazine.org/content/unconventional-wisdom/how-red-and-blue-map-evolved-over-past-century \"How the Red and Blue Map Evolved Over the Past Century\"]; ''America Magazine'' in ''The National Catholic Review''; June 29, 2016</ref> The last Democrat to win Russell County was [[Grover Cleveland]] in 1884, and the last Republican to not gain a majority was [[William Howard Taft]] in 1912 when his party was divided.\n{{Hidden begin\n|titlestyle = background:#ccccff;\n|title      = Presidential elections results\n}}\n{| align=\"center\" border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"float:right; margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n|+ '''Presidential elections results'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://uselectionatlas.org/RESULTS|title=Dave Leip's Atlas of U.S. Presidential Elections|last=Leip|first=David|website=uselectionatlas.org|access-date=2018-07-06}}</ref>\n|- bgcolor=lightgrey\n! Year\n! [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n! [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n! [[Third Party (United States)|Third parties]]\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''[[2016 Un