on|1912]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''43.3%''' ''785''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|39.4% ''713''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|17.3% ''314''\n|}\n{{Hidden end}}\n\n==Communities==\n* [[Creelsboro, Kentucky|Creelsboro]]\n* [[Jamestown, Kentucky|Jamestown]] (county seat)\n* [[Russell Springs, Kentucky|Russell Springs]]\n\n==Notable people==\n{{col div}}\n* [[Tara Conner]], [[Miss Kentucky USA]] 2006, [[Miss USA 2006]]\n* [[Vernie McGaha]], Former [[Kentucky State Senator]]\n* [[Doug Moseley]], later a [[Kentucky State Senate|Kentucky state senator]], was pastor of the Russell Springs First United Methodist Church from 1958 to 1960\n* [[Steve Wariner]], country music singer and songwriter. Kentucky State Route 80 is named in his honor.\n* [[Jeff Hoover]],  Republican member of the Kentucky House of Representatives, elected Speaker in late 2016.\n{{col div end}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|United States}}\n* [[National Register of Historic Places listings in Russell County, Kentucky]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.rcidaky.com/ Russell County Industrial Development Authority]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070210131524/http://www.kentuckyhighlands.com/kh/counties/russell_county.asp The Kentucky Highlands Project]\n* [http://www.russellcountylibrary.com/ Russell County Public Library]\n\n{{Russell County, Kentucky}}\n{{Kentucky}}\n\n{{Coord|36.99|-85.06|display=title|type:adm2nd_region:US-KY_source:UScensus1990}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Kentucky counties]]\n[[Category:Russell County, Kentucky| ]]\n[[Category:1825 establishments in Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1825]]\n[[Category:Counties of Appalachia]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toCommonwealth (disambiguation)(link changed toCommonwealth (U.S. state)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Russell_County,_Kentucky"}
{"title_page": "Franklin Brownell", "text_new": "{{Infobox artist\n| name          = Franklin Brownell\n| image         = Franklin Brownell - Peche sur glace, collines de la Gatineau, 1915.jpg\n| caption       = Franklin Brownell - Peche sur glace, collines de la Gatineau, 1915\n| birth_name     = Peleg Franklin Brownell<ref name=\"stacey\" /><ref name=\"loc\" /><ref name=\"national\" />\n| birth_date     = July 27, 1857\n| birth_place      = New Bedford, Massachusetts\n| death_date     = March 13, 1946\n| death_place    = [[Ottawa]] \n| nationality   = Canadian\n| field         = [[Painting]]\n| training      =  [[Tufts School of the Museum of Fine Arts|Boston School of the Museum of Fine Arts]],<br />[[Acad\u00e9mie Julian]]\n| movement      =\n| works  = }}\n\n'''Franklin Brownell''' (born '''Peleg Franklin Brownell''',<ref name=\"stacey\">{{cite web |last1=Stacey |first1=Robert |title=Peleg Franklin Brownell |date=March 4, 2015|url=https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/peleg-franklin-brownell |website=www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca |publisher=[[The Canadian Encyclopedia]] |accessdate=22 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"loc\">{{cite web |title=Brownell, Franklin (Peleg Franklin), 1856 or 1857-1946 |date=March 15, 2013|url=http://id.loc.gov/authorities/names/nr93012890.html |website=www.loc.gov |publisher=[[Library of Congress]] |accessdate=22 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"national\">{{cite web |title=Franklin Brownell : clippings file : Biographical Form 1920 |url=http://library.gallery.ca/record=b1225241~S4.( |date=2017|website=www.gallery.ca |publisher=[[National Gallery of Canada]] |accessdate=22 April 2020}}</ref> also known as '''Franklin Peleg Brownell''') (July 27, 1857 \u2013 March 13, 1946) born in [[New Bedford, Massachusetts]] was a [[landscape painter]], [[Drawing|draughtsman]] and teacher active in Canada.\n\n== Biography ==\nBrownell studied at the Boston [[School of the Museum of Fine Arts at Tufts|Tufts School of the Museum of Fine Arts]] in 1879 and at the [[Acad\u00e9mie Julian]] in Paris from 1880 to 1883 under [[William-Adolphe Bouguereau]], [[Tony Robert-Fleury]] and [[L\u00e9on Bonnat]]. There he met fellow expatriate and Canadian painter [[William Brymner]].\nAfter spending some time in [[Montreal]], Brownell moved to [[Ottawa]] in 1886 to take up the position of Headmaster of the [[Ottawa School of Art]] until 1900. He accepted the same position as headmaster between 1900 and 1937 with the Women\u2019s Art Association in Ottawa, later renamed the Art Association of Ottawa.<ref name=\"oup\">{{cite web|url=http://oxfordindex.oup.com/view/10.1093/benz/9780199773787.article.B00027322|publisher=oxfordindex.oup.com|title=Brownell, Franklin Peleg (1856 - 1946), Painter : Benezit Dictionary of Artists |accessdate=2016-11-20}}</ref>\nAmong his students were [[Pegi Nicol MacLeod]], Henri Masson and [[R. Tait McKenzie|Robert Tait McKenzie]].\n\nBrownell was elected a member of the [[Royal Canadian Academy of Arts]] in 1895, and the [[Ontario Society of Artists]] in 1899. He was also a founding member of the [[Canadian Art Club]] in [[Toronto]] in 1907. Through the Club, he became friendly with Maurice Cullen and James Wilson Morrice. As a result, his palette began to lighten. His most impressionist paintings were painted on several trips to the West Indies between 1911 and 1915.<ref>{{cite book|last=Prakash |first=A.K. |title=Impressionism in Canada: A Journey of Rediscovery |location=Stuttgart |publisher=Arnoldsche Art Publishers |date=2015 |pages=398-417 |isbn=978-3-89790-427-9|url=https://books.google.se/books?id=J-ZvrgEACAAJ&dq=}}</ref>\n\nOther painting trips he took were to the [[Gasp\u00e9sie\u2013\u00celes-de-la-Madeleine|Gasp\u00e9]] and [[Gatineau]] regions of [[Quebec]], to [[Algonquin Provincial Park]] and other areas around Ottawa in [[Ontario]].\n \nBesides landscapes, he  also produced [[portrait]]s, flower studies, [[Marine art|marine]] and [[Genre painting|genre scenes]] in [[Oil painting|\noil]], [[Watercolor painting|watercolour]] and [[pastel]].<ref name=\"stacey\" />\n\n== Exhibitions ==\n* 1893 Chicago [[World's Columbian Exposition]]\n* 1900 he won a bronze medal at the [[Exposition Universelle (1900)|Paris World's Fair exhibition]] for ''the photographer''\n* 1904, [[Louisiana Purchase Exhibition]], St Louis,\n* In 1922, he was honored with a [[retrospective]] exhibition of his work at the [[National Gallery of Canada]].\n* 1924\u201325, [[British Empire Exhibition]], 1924\u201325\n\n== Collections ==\n* [[National Gallery of Canada]]<ref name=\"gallery\">[https://www.gallery.ca/search/node/Franklin%20Brownell Mus\u00e9e des beaux-arts du Canada] accessdate 2016-11-20</ref>\n* [[Winnipeg Art Gallery]] <ref name=\"wag\">{{cite web|url=http://wag.ca/art/art-search/display,result/54375|publisher=wag.ca|title=Art Search &#124; Winnipeg Art Gallery|accessdate=2016-11-20}}</ref>\n* [[Mus\u00e9e d\u2019Orsay]] <ref name=\"musee-orsay\">{{cite web|url=http://www.musee-orsay.fr/fr/espace-professionnels/professionnels/chercheurs/rech-rec-art-home/notice-artiste.html?nnumid=114421|publisher=musee-orsay.fr|title=Mus\u00e9e d'Orsay: Notice d'Artiste n\u00b0 114421 Franklin Brownell |accessdate=2016-11-20}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n*{{cite book \n|last1=Burant \n|first1=James \n|last2=Stacey \n|first2=Robert H. \n|title=North by South : the art of Peleg Franklin Brownell, 1857-1946 = Du Nord et du Sud : l'art de Peleg Franklin Brownell, 1857-1946. \n|date=1998 \n|publisher=[[Ottawa Art Gallery]] \n|location=Ottawa \n|isbn=1895108497 \n|url=https://search.library.utoronto.ca/details?2164437&uuid=17bf8ada-9b05-451f-97ab-0caa5229a8ae\n|postscript= Catalogue of a retrospective exhibition held at the Ottawa Art Gallery, July 16 to Sept. 13, 1998.\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.klinkhoff.ca/search/?search=Franklin+Brownell Franklin Brownell on klinkhoff.ca]\n* [[Valentin Gallery]]: [http://www.galerievalentin.com/contemporary-artists/franklin-brownell/biography.php  Edmond Dyonnet ''Franklin Brownell Biography'']\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Canada|Visual arts}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brownell, Franklin}}\n[[Category:1857 births]]\n[[Category:1946 deaths]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Acad\u00e9mie Julian]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian painters]]\n[[Category:Canadian male painters]]\n[[Category:Members of the Royal Canadian Academy of Arts]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox artist\n| name          = Franklin Brownell\n| image         = Franklin Brownell - Peche sur glace, collines de la Gatineau, 1915.jpg\n| caption       = Franklin Brownell - Peche sur glace, collines de la Gatineau, 1915\n| birth_name     = Peleg Franklin Brownell<ref name=\"stacey\" /><ref name=\"loc\" /><ref name=\"national\" />\n| birth_date     = July 27, 1857\n| birth_place      = New Bedford, Massachusetts\n| death_date     = March 13, 1946\n| death_place    = [[Ottawa]] \n| nationality   = Canadian\n| field         = [[Painting]]\n| training      =  [[Tufts School of the Museum of Fine Arts|Boston School of the Museum of Fine Arts]],<br />[[Acad\u00e9mie Julian]]\n| movement      =\n| works  = }}\n\n'''Franklin Brownell''' (born '''Peleg Franklin Brownell''',<ref name=\"stacey\">{{cite web |last1=Stacey |first1=Robert |title=Peleg Franklin Brownell |date=March 4, 2015|url=https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/peleg-franklin-brownell |website=www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca |publisher=[[The Canadian Encyclopedia]] |accessdate=22 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"loc\">{{cite web |title=Brownell, Franklin (Peleg Franklin), 1856 or 1857-1946 |date=March 15, 2013|url=http://id.loc.gov/authorities/names/nr93012890.html |website=www.loc.gov |publisher=[[Library of Congress]] |accessdate=22 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"national\">{{cite web |title=Franklin Brownell : clippings file |url=http://library.gallery.ca/record=b1225241~S4.( |date=2017|website=www.gallery.ca |publisher=[[National Gallery of Canada]] |accessdate=22 April 2020}}</ref> also known as '''Franklin Peleg Brownell''') (July 27, 1857 \u2013 March 13, 1946) born in [[New Bedford, Massachusetts]] was a [[landscape painter]], [[Drawing|draughtsman]] and teacher active in Canada.\n\n== Biography ==\nBrownell studied at the Boston [[School of the Museum of Fine Arts at Tufts|Tufts School of the Museum of Fine Arts]] in 1879 and at the [[Acad\u00e9mie Julian]] in Paris from 1880 to 1883 under [[William-Adolphe Bouguereau]], [[Tony Robert-Fleury]] and [[L\u00e9on Bonnat]]. There he met fellow expatriate and Canadian painter [[William Brymner]].\nAfter spending some time in [[Montreal]], Brownell moved to [[Ottawa]] in 1886 to take up the position of Headmaster of the [[Ottawa School of Art]] until 1900. He accepted the same position as headmaster between 1900 and 1937 with the Women\u2019s Art Association in Ottawa, later renamed the Art Association of Ottawa.<ref name=\"oup\">{{cite web|url=http://oxfordindex.oup.com/view/10.1093/benz/9780199773787.article.B00027322|publisher=oxfordindex.oup.com|title=Brownell, Franklin Peleg (1856 - 1946), Painter : Benezit Dictionary of Artists |accessdate=2016-11-20}}</ref>\nAmong his students were [[Pegi Nicol MacLeod]], Henri Masson and [[R. Tait McKenzie|Robert Tait McKenzie]].\n\nBrownell was elected a member of the [[Royal Canadian Academy of Arts]] in 1895, and the [[Ontario Society of Artists]] in 1899. He was also a founding member of the [[Canadian Art Club]] in [[Toronto]] in 1907. Through the Club, he became friendly with Maurice Cullen and James Wilson Morrice. As a result, his palette began to lighten. His most impressionist paintings were painted on several trips to the West Indies between 1911 and 1915.<ref>{{cite book|last=Prakash |first=A.K. |title=Impressionism in Canada: A Journey of Rediscovery |location=Stuttgart |publisher=Arnoldsche Art Publishers |date=2015 |pages=398-417 |isbn=978-3-89790-427-9|url=https://books.google.se/books?id=J-ZvrgEACAAJ&dq=}}</ref>\n\nOther painting trips he took were to the [[Gasp\u00e9sie\u2013\u00celes-de-la-Madeleine|Gasp\u00e9]] and [[Gatineau]] regions of [[Quebec]], to [[Algonquin Provincial Park]] and other areas around Ottawa in [[Ontario]].\n \nBesides landscapes, he  also produced [[portrait]]s, flower studies, [[Marine art|marine]] and [[Genre painting|genre scenes]] in [[Oil painting|\noil]], [[Watercolor painting|watercolour]] and [[pastel]].<ref name=\"stacey\" />\n\n== Exhibitions ==\n* 1893 Chicago [[World's Columbian Exposition]]\n* 1900 he won a bronze medal at the [[Exposition Universelle (1900)|Paris World's Fair exhibition]] for ''the photographer''\n* 1904, [[Louisiana Purchase Exhibition]], St Louis,\n* In 1922, he was honored with a [[retrospective]] exhibition of his work at the [[National Gallery of Canada]].\n* 1924\u201325, [[British Empire Exhibition]], 1924\u201325\n\n== Collections ==\n* [[National Gallery of Canada]]<ref name=\"gallery\">[https://www.gallery.ca/search/node/Franklin%20Brownell Mus\u00e9e des beaux-arts du Canada] accessdate 2016-11-20</ref>\n* [[Winnipeg Art Gallery]] <ref name=\"wag\">{{cite web|url=http://wag.ca/art/art-search/display,result/54375|publisher=wag.ca|title=Art Search &#124; Winnipeg Art Gallery|accessdate=2016-11-20}}</ref>\n* [[Mus\u00e9e d\u2019Orsay]] <ref name=\"musee-orsay\">{{cite web|url=http://www.musee-orsay.fr/fr/espace-professionnels/professionnels/chercheurs/rech-rec-art-home/notice-artiste.html?nnumid=114421|publisher=musee-orsay.fr|title=Mus\u00e9e d'Orsay: Notice d'Artiste n\u00b0 114421 Franklin Brownell |accessdate=2016-11-20}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n*{{cite book \n|last1=Burant \n|first1=James \n|last2=Stacey \n|first2=Robert H. \n|title=North by South : the art of Peleg Franklin Brownell, 1857-1946 = Du Nord et du Sud : l'art de Peleg Franklin Brownell, 1857-1946. \n|date=1998 \n|publisher=[[Ottawa Art Gallery]] \n|location=Ottawa \n|isbn